# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: advokat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:advokat/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:advokat/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:advokat/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:advokat/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:advokat/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:advokat/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:advokat/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:advokat/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:advokat/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:advokat/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:advokat/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:advokat/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:advokat/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:advokat/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:advokat/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:advokat/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:advokat/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:advokat/advocate] An **advocate** is a professional in the field of law.
[src:advokat/advocate] Different countries and legal systems use the term with somewhat differing meanings.
[src:advokat/advocate] The broad equivalent in many English law–based jurisdictions could be a barrister or a solicitor.
[src:advokat/advocate] However, in Scottish, Manx, South African, Italian, French, Spanish, Portuguese, Scandinavian, Polish, Israeli, South Asian and South American jurisdictions, "advocate" indicates a lawyer of superior classification.
[src:advokat/advocate] "Advocate" is in some languages an honorific for lawyers, such as "Adv.
[src:advokat/advocate] "Advocate" also has the everyday meaning of speaking out to help someone else, such as patient advocacy or the support expected from an elected politician; this article does not cover those senses.
[src:advokat/advocate] In England and Wales, advocates and proctors practiced civil law in the Admiralty Courts and also, but in England only, in the ecclesiastical courts of the Church of England, in a similar way to barristers, attorneys and solicitors in the common law and equity courts.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates, who formed the senior branch of the legal profession in their field, were Doctors of Law of the University of Oxford, Cambridge, or Dublin and Fellows of the Society of Doctors' Commons.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates lost their exclusive rights of audience in probate and divorce cases when the Crown took these matters over from the church in 1857, and in Admiralty cases in 1859.
[src:advokat/advocate] The Society of Advocates was never formally wound up, but its building was sold off in 1865 and the last advocate died in 1912.
[src:advokat/advocate] Barristers were admitted to the Court of Arches of the Church of England in 1867.
[src:advokat/advocate] More recently, Solicitor Advocates have also been allowed to play this role.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates are regulated by the Faculty of Advocates in Edinburgh.
[src:advokat/advocate] The Faculty of Advocates has about 750 members, of whom about 460 are in private practice.
[src:advokat/advocate] The Faculty is headed by the Dean of the Faculty who, along with the Vice-Dean, Treasurer, and Clerk are elected annually by secret ballot.
[src:advokat/advocate] The Faculty has a service company, Faculty Services Ltd, to which almost all Advocates belong, which organized the **stables** (sets of Advocates or barristers' chambers) and fee collection.
[src:advokat/advocate] This gives a guarantee to all newly called Advocates of a place.
[src:advokat/advocate] Until the end of 2007, there was an agreement with the Law Society of Scotland, which is the professional body for Scottish solicitors, as to the payment of fees, but this has now been replaced by the Law Society.
[src:advokat/advocate] It remains the case that Advocates are not permitted to sue for their fees, as they have no contractual relationship with their instructing solicitor or with the client.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates wear wigs, white bow-ties (or falls in the case of senior counsel), straps and gowns as a dress in court.
[src:advokat/advocate] The process of becoming an advocate is referred to as devilling.
[src:advokat/advocate] At the end of the devilling period, a devil's admission to the Faculty is dependent on certification by the principal devil master that the devil is a fit and proper person to be an advocate and that the devil has been involved in a wide range of work in the course of devilling.
[src:advokat/advocate] A devil's competence in a number of aspects of written and oral advocacy is assessed during devilling, and a devil will not be admitted to the Faculty if assessed as not competent.
[src:advokat/advocate] Further details of this process can be found in the assessment section.
[src:advokat/advocate] In recent years, increasing numbers of Advocates have come to the Scottish Bar after some time as solicitors, but it is possible to qualify with a law degree, after twenty-one months traineeship in a solicitor's office and almost a year as a 'devil', or apprentice advocate.
[src:advokat/advocate] There are exceptions for lawyers who are qualified in other European jurisdictions, but all must take the training course as 'devils'.
[src:advokat/advocate] Until 2007, a number of young European lawyers were given a placement with Advocates under the European Young Lawyers Scheme organized by the British Council.
[src:advokat/advocate] They are known as 'Eurodevils', in distinction to the Scottish 'devils'.
[src:advokat/advocate] This scheme was withdrawn by the British Council.
[src:advokat/advocate] In January 2009, a replacement scheme began.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates share the right of audience with solicitors in the sheriff courts and justice of the peace courts.
[src:advokat/advocate] However, the seven-judge English ruling of *Arthur J.S.
[src:advokat/advocate] Simons* 2000 (House of Lords) declared that none of these reasons justified the immunity strongly enough to sustain it.
[src:advokat/advocate] This has been followed in Scotland in *Wright v Paton Farrell* (2006) *obiter* insofar as civil cases are concerned.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates are the only lawyers with rights of audience in the courts of the Isle of Man.
[src:advokat/advocate] An advocate's role is to advise on all matters of law: it may involve representing a client in the civil and criminal courts or advising a client on matters such as matrimonial and family law, trusts and estates, regulatory matters, property transactions, and commercial and business law.
[src:advokat/advocate] In court, Advocates wear a horsehair wig, stiff collar, bands, and a gown in the same way as barristers do elsewhere.
[src:advokat/advocate] To become an advocate, it is normally necessary to hold either a qualifying law degree with no less than lower second class (2:2) honors, or else a degree in another subject with no less than lower second class (2:2) honors complemented by the Common Professional Examination.
[src:advokat/advocate] It is then necessary to obtain a legal professional qualification such as the Bar Professional Training Course or the Legal Practice Course.
[src:advokat/advocate] It is not, however, necessary actually to be admitted as an English barrister or solicitor to train as an advocate.
[src:advokat/advocate] Trainee Advocates (as articled clerks are now more usually known) normally undertake a period of two years' training articled to a senior advocate; in the case of English barristers or solicitors who have been practicing or admitted for three years this training, the period is reduced to one year.
[src:advokat/advocate] Foreign lawyers who have been registered as legal practitioners in the Isle of Man for a certain time may also undertake a shorter period of training and supervision.
[src:advokat/advocate] During their training, all trainee Advocates are required to pass the Isle of Man bar examinations, which include papers on civil and criminal practice, constitutional and land law, and company law and taxation, as well as accounts.
[src:advokat/advocate] The examinations are rigorous and candidates are limited to three attempts to pass each paper.
[src:advokat/advocate] Senior English barristers are occasionally licensed to appear as Advocates in cases expected to be unusually long or complex, without having to pass the bar examination or undertake further training: they are permitted only to act in relation to the matter for which they have been licensed.
[src:advokat/advocate] Similarly, barristers and solicitors employed as public prosecutors may be licensed to appear as Advocates without having to pass the bar examination or undertake further training: they are permitted only to act as such only for the duration of that employment.
[src:advokat/advocate] The professional conduct of Advocates is regulated by the Isle of Man Law Society, which also maintains a library for its members in Douglas.
[src:advokat/advocate] While Advocates in the Isle of Man have not traditionally prefixed their names with 'Advocate' in the Channel Islands manner, some Advocates have now started to adopt this practice.
[src:advokat/advocate] Jersey and the Bailiwick of Guernsey are two separate legal jurisdictions, have largely two different sets of laws and have two separate, but similar, legal professions.
[src:advokat/advocate] In both jurisdictions, Advocates—properly called Advocates of the Royal Court—are the only lawyers with general rights of audience in their courts.
[src:advokat/advocate] To be eligible to practice as an advocate in Jersey, it is necessary first to have a law degree from a British university or a Graduate Diploma in Law and to have qualified as a recognized legal professional in England and Wales, Scotland or Northern Ireland.
[src:advokat/advocate] Thereafter, a candidate must undertake two years of practical experience in a law office dealing with Jersey law, enrol on the Jersey Law Course provided by the Institute of Law, Jersey and pass examinations in six subjects.
[src:advokat/advocate] Alternatively, a person may apply to become a Jersey advocate two years after qualifying as a Jersey solicitor.
[src:advokat/advocate] To become an advocate in Guernsey, one has to possess a valid law degree or diploma, plus a qualification as an English barrister or solicitor, or a French avocat.
[src:advokat/advocate] They must then study for the Guernsey Bar.
[src:advokat/advocate] Three months of study of Norman law at the Université de Caen (University of Caen) is required; this is no longer required for entry into the legal profession in Jersey.
[src:advokat/advocate] Guernsey Advocates dress in the same way as barristers, but substitute a black biretta-like toque for a wig, while those in Jersey go bare-headed.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates are entitled to prefix their names with 'Advocate'; e.g.
[src:advokat/advocate] Tostevin is called to the Guernsey Bar and is henceforth known as Advocate Tostevin.
[src:advokat/advocate] The head of the profession of advocate in each bailiwick is called the Bâtonnier.
[src:advokat/advocate] In the Netherlands, the professional conduct and the professional education of the advocates is regulated by the Dutch bar association (Nederlandse orde van advocaten) pursuant to the Advocates Act (*Advocatenwet*).
[src:advokat/advocate] Dutch advocates are admitted to the bar conditionally, and have full rights of audience with the district courts and court of appeal.
[src:advokat/advocate] During this time, the advocate is referred to as an *advocaat-stagiair(e)*.
[src:advokat/advocate] In court, advocates must wear a long black robe (a *toga*) and a white pleated band (a *bef*).
[src:advokat/advocate] The Nordic countries have a united legal profession, which means that they do not draw a distinction between lawyers who plead in court and those who do not.
[src:advokat/advocate] To get an official recognition with an Advocates title, the candidate must have a legal degree, that is, completed ca.
[src:advokat/advocate] 5–6 years of legal studies from an accredited university in his or own country, and in addition have worked for some time (around 2 – 5 years) under the auspices of a qualified advocate and have some experience from court.
[src:advokat/advocate] When qualified, the candidate may obtain a license as an *advocate*, the equivalent of being called to the bar.
[src:advokat/advocate] In all the Scandinavian languages the title is *advokat*; in Finland *advokat* is the Swedish title for such a qualified lawyer, with the equivalent title in Finnish being *asianajaja*.
[src:advokat/advocate] However, one does not necessarily have to be an advocate to represent a party in the Nordic countries legally.
[src:advokat/advocate] In Norway, a person with an appropriate law degree, for example, can practice law as a registered legal advisor (*rettshjelper*) instead, which gives many of the same rights as an advocate's title.
[src:advokat/advocate] Both in Sweden and Norway any adult, in theory, can represent a party in court without any prior approval, training, license or advocate title.
[src:advokat/advocate] In practice it's unusual, and in Norway, it's subject to the approval of the court, which is unlikely to give it except in very simple cases.
[src:advokat/advocate] In English, the Scandinavian title of *advokat* is interchangeably also translated as barrister, lawyer or attorney-at-law.
[src:advokat/advocate] Specialist degree in law is the most commonly awarded academic degree in Russian jurisprudence but after Russia's accession to the Bologna process only bachelor of laws and master of laws academic degrees are available in Russian institutions of higher education.
[src:advokat/advocate] An "advocate" is a lawyer who has demonstrated qualification and belongs to an organizational structure of Advocates specified by law, known as being "called to the bar" in Commonwealth countries.
[src:advokat/advocate] An examination is administered by the qualifications commission of regional advocate's chamber for admission to its **Advokatura**.
[src:advokat/advocate] To sit for the exam, one must have a higher legal education and also two years of experience in legal work after graduation or a training program in a law firm after graduation.
[src:advokat/advocate] The exam is both written and oral, but the main test is oral.
[src:advokat/advocate] The written exam takes place in the form of computer testing and includes issues of the professional conduct of advocate and advocate's professional responsibility.
[src:advokat/advocate] After successfully passing of the written exam the candidates are allowed to take the oral exam.
[src:advokat/advocate] As part of the oral exam, the candidate must demonstrate his knowledge in various bodies of law and solve some mimic a real-life legal tasks.
[src:advokat/advocate] The candidate who does not pass the qualification exam can try to pass it again after 1 year only.
[src:advokat/advocate] The qualifications commission is composed of seven Advocates, two judges, two representatives of the regional legislature, and two representatives of the Ministry of Justice.
[src:advokat/advocate] After successful passing the qualification exam a candidate should take the oath of advocate.
[src:advokat/advocate] From the moment of taking the oath, he becomes an advocate and a member of the advocate's chamber of the relevant federal subject of Russia.
[src:advokat/advocate] The status of an advocate is granted for an indefinite period and is not limited by any age.
[src:advokat/advocate] There is only 1 advocate's chamber in each federal subject of Russia.
[src:advokat/advocate] Each advocate can be the member of only 1 advocate's chamber and can be listed in the register of Advocates of the relevant federal subject of Russia only.
[src:advokat/advocate] Each advocate can carry out his professional activity throughout Russia, regardless of membership in particular regional advocate's chamber and regardless of particular regional register where he is listed in.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates carry out their professional activity individually (advocate's cabinet) or as the member of advocate's juridical person (collegium of Advocates, advocate's bureau).
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocate can open own cabinet after at least 3 years legal practice in collegium or bureau.
[src:advokat/advocate] An advocate, who has opened own cabinet, can not be the member of any advocate's juridical person, and an advocate, who is the member of one advocate's juridical person, can not be the member of any other advocate's juridical person.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocate is obliged to report to advocate's chamber any changes in his membership in a collegium or a bureau and, equally, opening and closing a cabinet.
[src:advokat/advocate] An advocate can not be an individual entrepreneur, government official, municipal official, notary, judge, elected official.
[src:advokat/advocate] An advocate can not work under an employment (labour) contract, with the exception of scientific and teaching activities.
[src:advokat/advocate] An advocate may combine his status with the status of a patent attorney, a trustee in bankruptcy.
[src:advokat/advocate] An advocate may be a shareholder/owner of business juridical persons and a member of voluntary associations and political parties.
[src:advokat/advocate] Russian advocate may have a status of advocate (attorney, barrister, solicitor) in foreign jurisdiction, subject to above conditions.
[src:advokat/advocate] Russian law provides for voluntary and involuntary suspension of advocate's status.
[src:advokat/advocate] Voluntary suspension for a term of 1 to 10 years occurs when an Advocate files relevant application to the advocate's chamber.
[src:advokat/advocate] Involuntary suspension is applicable in cases of serious illness, election to an elected position in federal, regional or local authorities, military conscription, declaration of absence made by the court decision.
[src:advokat/advocate] An Advocate can not carry out advocate's activity during suspension, otherwise he may be deprived of the right to be an Advocate.
[src:advokat/advocate] After the end of the suspension, advocate's status should be resumed without any additional conditions.
[src:advokat/advocate] Also Russian law provides for voluntary and involuntary termination of advocate's status.
[src:advokat/advocate] Voluntary termination of the status occurs when an Advocate files relevant application to the advocate's chamber.
[src:advokat/advocate] The latter two cases incur lifetime prohibition on being an Advocate.
[src:advokat/advocate] In other cases, ex-Advocate can go back to being an Advocate on general grounds through a passing the qualification exam, on condition that the reasons for termination of advocate's status have ceased to exist.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocate's chambers are professional associations of Advocates, which are based on mandatory membership of Advocates.
[src:advokat/advocate] All regional advocate's chambers are mandatory members of Federal Chamber of Advocates of Russian Federation (Russian: Федеральная палата адвокатов Российской Федерации), which is professional association at the federal level.
[src:advokat/advocate] As of 2018, there were 49,4 Advocates per 100,000 people in Russia.
[src:advokat/advocate] In Russia, foreign Advocates can advise on the legislation of their countries; they should register in the special register maintained by the Ministry of Justice of the Russian Federation to obtain the right to carry out this activity.
[src:advokat/advocate] Foreign advocate can in addition become Russian advocate.
[src:advokat/advocate] Since Russia's WTO Accession the second possibility is available: foreign advocate can just pass special qualification exam to become Russian advocate.
[src:advokat/advocate] In Bangladesh, after passing the Higher Secondary School Certificate, one can apply for admission for studying law in Universities.
[src:advokat/advocate] There are several public and private universities which provide Bachelor of Laws and Master of Laws degree in Bangladesh.
[src:advokat/advocate] Generally, the LL.B. course is equivalent to a four-year bachelor's degree.
[src:advokat/advocate] Graduate lawyers have to seat for and pass the Bar Council Exam to become Advocates.
[src:advokat/advocate] By passing the Bangladesh Bar Council Exam, Advocates are eligible to practice in the Supreme Court of Bangladesh and other courts.
[src:advokat/advocate] A license is obtained after successful completion of two year's practice in the lower courts by applicant, which is reviewed by a body of the relevant provincial Bar Council.
[src:advokat/advocate] Most applications after successful completion of the requirement, are accepted.
[src:advokat/advocate] In India, the law relating to the Advocates is the Advocates Act, 1961 introduced and thought up by Ashoke Kumar Sen, the then law minister of India, which is a law passed by the Parliament and is administered and enforced by the Bar Council of India.
[src:advokat/advocate] Under the Act, the Bar Council of India is the supreme regulatory body to regulate the legal profession in India and also to ensure the compliance of the laws and maintenance of professional standards by the legal profession in the country.
[src:advokat/advocate] Each State has a Bar Council of its own whose function is to enroll the Advocates willing to practice predominantly within the territorial confines of that State and to perform the functions of the Bar Council of India within the territory assigned to them.
[src:advokat/advocate] Therefore, each law degree holder must be enrolled with a (single) State Bar Council to practice in India.
[src:advokat/advocate] However, enrollment with any State Bar Council does not restrict the Advocate from appearing before any court in India, even though it is beyond the territorial jurisdiction of the State Bar Council which he is enrolled in.
[src:advokat/advocate] The advantage of having the State Bar Councils is that the workload of the Bar Council of India can be divided into these various State Bar Councils and also that matters can be dealt with locally and in an expedited manner.
[src:advokat/advocate] However, for all practical and legal purposes, the Bar Council of India retains with it, the final power to take decisions in any and all matters related to the legal profession on the whole or with respect to any Advocate individually, as so provided under the Advocates Act, 1961.
[src:advokat/advocate] The process of being entitled to practice in India is twofold.
[src:advokat/advocate] First, the applicant must be a holder of a law degree from a recognised institution in India (or from one of the four recognised Universities in the United Kingdom) and second, must pass the enrollment qualifications of the Bar Council of the state where he/she seeks to be enrolled.
[src:advokat/advocate] For this purpose, the Bar Council of India has an internal Committee whose function is to supervise and examine the various institutions conferring law degrees and to grant recognition to these institutions once they meet the required standards.
[src:advokat/advocate] In this manner, the Bar Council of India also ensures the standard of education required for practicing in India is met with.
[src:advokat/advocate] As regards the qualification for enrollment with the State Bar Council, while the actual formalities may vary from one State to another, yet predominately they ensure that the application has not been a bankrupt /criminal and is generally fit to practice before courts of India.
[src:advokat/advocate] Enrollment with a Bar Council also means that the law degree holder is recognised as an Advocate and is required to maintain a standard of conduct and professional demeanor at all times, both on and off the profession.
[src:advokat/advocate] The Bar Council of India also prescribes "Rules of Conduct" to be observed by the Advocates in the courts, while interacting with clients and even otherwise.
[src:advokat/advocate] All Advocates in India are at the same level and are recognised as such.
[src:advokat/advocate] Any distinction, if any, is made only on the basis of seniority, which implies the length of practice at the Bar.
[src:advokat/advocate] As a recognition of law practice and specialisation in an area of law, there is a concept of conferral of Senior Advocate status.
[src:advokat/advocate] An Advocate may be recognised by the Judges of the High Court (in case of an Advocate practicing before that High Court) or by the Supreme Court (in case of the Advocate practicing before the Supreme Court).
[src:advokat/advocate] While the conferral of Senior Advocate status not only implies distinction and fame of the Advocate, it also requires the Senior Advocate to follow higher standards of conduct and some distinct rules.
[src:advokat/advocate] Also, a Senior Advocate is not allowed to interact directly with the clients.
[src:advokat/advocate] He can only take briefs from other Advocates and argue on the basis of the details given by them.
[src:advokat/advocate] From the year 2010 onward a mandatory rule is made for lawyers passing out from the year 2009–10 to sit for an evaluation test named AIBE (All India Bar Exam) for one to qualify as an advocate and practice in the courts.
[src:advokat/advocate] However, to practice law before the Supreme Court of India, Advocates must first appear for and qualify in the Supreme Court Advocate on Record Examination conducted by the Supreme Court.
[src:advokat/advocate] Further, under the Constitutional structure, there is a provision for the elevation of Advocates as judges of High Courts and Supreme Court.
[src:advokat/advocate] The only requirement is the Advocate must have ten years standing before the High Court(/s) or before the Supreme Court to be eligible for such.
[src:advokat/advocate] There are four levels of Advocates exist in Pakistan, 1.
[src:advokat/advocate] The first level is that of an Advocate, who is eligible to practice in the district courts or lower courts in their respective province.
[src:advokat/advocate] An Advocate is considered an officer of the court.
[src:advokat/advocate] To become an Advocate, one can qualify by completing a five-year law degree (LL.B (Hons)), or by obtaining a foreign LL.B degree of a shorter duration, recognized by the relevant authorities.
[src:advokat/advocate] Additionally, they must complete six months of pupillage under a senior Advocate in their chambers.
[src:advokat/advocate] Afterward, they are required to pass a GAT test recognized by the Higher Education Commission of Pakistan (HEC) and the Pakistan Bar Council, achieving a minimum passing score of 50%.
[src:advokat/advocate] Subsequently, they must successfully clear the Bar admission test and undergo an examination conducted by the Bar Council of their respective province to determine their suitability for becoming an Advocate and confirm that they have no criminal convictions.
[src:advokat/advocate] Upon passing a multiple-choice question examination and an interview conducted by members of the provincial Bar Council, the Bar Council will issue them a license to practice before the Subordinate Courts up to the High Court.
[src:advokat/advocate] After completing two years of practice as an Advocate, with a minimum of ten successfully litigated cases, the Advocate will be required to submit a list of these cases for examination by a committee appointed by the High Court.
[src:advokat/advocate] The committee, chaired by a High Court Judge, will review the cases and, if satisfied, grant their approval for the Advocate's elevation to practice as an Advocate of the High Court.
[src:advokat/advocate] Upon approval, the committee will send the recommendation directly to the Bar Council, and the Advocate will be issued a license to practice as an Advocate of the High Court.
[src:advokat/advocate] As an Advocate of the High Court, they will have the right to practice in any court throughout the country, except for the Supreme Court of Pakistan.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocate Supreme Court is the third level.
[src:advokat/advocate] After successful completion of ten years of practice in the High Courts by the applicant, the panel of members of Pakistan Bar Council and one judge of the Supreme Court of Pakistan, review the application.
[src:advokat/advocate] (Before 1985 the requirement was successful completion of five years practice in the High Courts of Pakistan.) Over fifty per cent of applications are accepted, after successful completion of the requirement.
[src:advokat/advocate] An unsuccessful application in one year does not bar the candidate from re-applying in the next judicial year.
[src:advokat/advocate] The highest level is the Senior Advocate Supreme Court.
[src:advokat/advocate] It is Pakistan's title equivalent to Queen's Counsel in the United Kingdom.
[src:advokat/advocate] After at least fifteen years of practice, by invitation or by an application to a panel of Supreme Court Judges headed by the Chief Justice of Pakistan, one can become Senior Advocate of Supreme Court of Pakistan.
[src:advokat/advocate] Very few applications are accepted and even fewer invitations are made.
[src:advokat/advocate] Attorneys General are usually invited by the Supreme Court on the appointment, to the office.
[src:advokat/advocate] So are some notable High Court judges who upon retirement choose to practice before the Supreme Court, where they are still eligible to do so.
[src:advokat/advocate] In Sri Lanka (formally Ceylon) till 1973 Advocate was a practitioner in a court of law who is legally qualified to prosecute and defend actions in such court on the retainer of clients.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates had to pass the HSC exam and enter the Ceylon Law College and follow the Advocates course and sit for the relevant exams.
[src:advokat/advocate] Thereafter, they would have to practice under a senior advocate before being called to the bar for admission as an Advocate of the Supreme Court of Ceylon.
[src:advokat/advocate] Members of the English, Scottish and Irish Bars are permitted to be admitted to a Barrister without examination on payment of a fee.
[src:advokat/advocate] Ceylonese Advocates with three years standing were allowed to be called to the English Bar without examination on completing three terms.
[src:advokat/advocate] 44 of 1973* of the National State Assembly created a single group of practitioners known as Attorneys-at-law.
[src:advokat/advocate] The current equivalent to an advocate is a counsel who is a trial lawyer distinguished from an instructing attorney.
[src:advokat/advocate] In South Africa, there are two main branches of legal practitioner: attorneys, who do legal work of all kinds, and Advocates, who are specialist litigators; see Attorneys in South Africa.
[src:advokat/advocate] In general, Advocates (also called 'counsel') are 'briefed' by attorneys when a specialist skill in court-based litigation, or in research into the law (an opinion) is required.
[src:advokat/advocate] Referral Advocates thus have no direct contact with clients and are said to be in a 'referral' profession.
[src:advokat/advocate] However, Advocates who have a Trust Account and hold a valid Fidelity Fund Certificate are authorized to take briefs directly from the public and attorneys respectively.
[src:advokat/advocate] The key formal distinction, however, is the different rights with regard to the courts in which they may appear.
[src:advokat/advocate] Advocates have the right to appear in any court, while attorneys have the right to appear only in the lower courts.
[src:advokat/advocate] The requirements to enter private practice as Advocates (Junior Counsel) are to hold the LL.B. degree, and to become a member of a Bar Association by undergoing a period of training (pupilage) for one year with a practicing Advocate, and to sit an admission examination.
[src:advokat/advocate] On the recommendation of the Bar Councils, an advocate "of proven experience and skill" with at least ten years experience, may be appointed by the President of South Africa as a Senior Counsel (SC; also referred to as a "silk").
[src:advokat/advocate] Junior advocates are commonly rewarded with a traditional gift of a red brief bag by a Senior Counsel as recognition for excellence.
[src:advokat/advocate] In Brazil, the bar examination occurs nationally in March, August, and December.
[src:advokat/advocate] These examinations are unified and organized by the Order of Attorneys of Brazil.
[src:advokat/advocate] After 5 years in law school, Brazilian law students are required to take the bar exam, which consists of 2 phases: the multiple choice test and written test, without any further requirements.
[src:advokat/advocate] The Constitution of Brazil applies restrictions on professional practice of law in the fulfillment of the requirements, which may include in addition to graduation, formal submission of the applicant in the proficiency tests.
[src:advokat/advocate] Within its powers expressly granted by the Constitution, the ordinary legislative demands that whoever wishes to pursue the legal profession possess the degree of Bachelor of Law and approval of Examination of Order, whose preparation and implementation is done by their own class.
[src:advokat/advocate] The Constitution itself provides for the restriction, and the Statute of Law requires the examination.
[src:advokat/advocate] The bar exam in Brazil approves very few students and is considered a hard one.
[src:advokat/advocate] For instance, in February 2014, the Bar association made a release stating that only 19.64% of students had been approved in the last exam and were able to register as a lawyer.
[src:advokat/advokat] Authorization to practice as *advokat* traditionally required the candidate to graduate from law school as Candidate of Law followed by three years of employment with a law firm or other eligible institution.
[src:advokat/advokat] In recent years, candidates have also been required to undergo training and to pass a bar examination administered by Advokatsamfundet, the Danish Bar and Law Society.
[src:advokat/advokat] To practice law as an *advokat*, the lawyer must maintain a current membership with the Danish Bar and Law Society, which supervises its approximately 4,800 members.
[src:advokat/advokat] Apart from paying annual dues to the association, an *advokat* must also adhere to its professional code of conduct, and may face disciplinary action as a consequence of conduct deemed unprofessional by Advokatnævnet, the Disciplinary Board.
[src:advokat/advokat] As a result of legal reform implemented in recent years, there is no longer a monopoly held by those bearing the title *advokat* on providing most legal services in Denmark.
[src:advokat/advokat] Any lawyer applying for membership in the Finnish Bar Association must have completed a Master of Laws degree, entitling them to hold judicial office, and must be known to be a person of integrity.
[src:advokat/advokat] They also must have several years experience in the legal profession and other judicial duties.
[src:advokat/advokat] Only members of the bar association are entitled to use the Swedish language professional title *advokat* (fi.
[src:advokat/advokat] The Finnish Bar Association has about 1,570 members.
[src:advokat/advokat] A candidate seeking permission to practice from the Supervisory Authority for Legal Services (no.
[src:advokat/advokat] *Advokattilsynet*) is required to graduate from law school as a Candidate of Law, must be a person of integrity, must be at least 20 years of age, and must have practiced as a lawyer-in-training ("advokatfullmektig") for two years.
[src:advokat/advokat] Furthermore, the candidate must have represented clients in at least three court cases, of which one must be a civil case of a certain length, and of which one may be replaced by an exam by a certified provider.
[src:advokat/advokat] Only those authorized by the Supervisory Council are entitled to use the professional title *advokat* in Norway.
[src:advokat/advokat] To a certain extent, there is a monopoly held by those bearing the title *advokat* on providing legal services in Norwegian courts of law.
[src:advokat/advokat] A candidate seeking admittance to the Swedish Bar Association is required to graduate from law school as a Candidate of Law entitling the candidate to hold judicial office, must be a person of integrity, and must have practiced for three years.
[src:advokat/advokat] Only members of the bar association are entitled to use the professional title *advokat* in Sweden.
[src:advokat/advokat] The Swedish Bar Association has in excess of 4,400 members.
[src:advokat/advokat] In principle, there is no monopoly held by those bearing the title *advokat* on providing legal services in Sweden; a person may appoint almost anyone as *ombud* (representative) whether in civil, tort or criminal proceedings.
[src:advokat/advokat] However, if a defendant wishes to recoup expenses, the *ombud* typically needs to be an approved member of the SBA.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] A **bar examination** is an examination administered by the bar association of a jurisdiction that a lawyer must pass in order to be admitted to the bar of that jurisdiction.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Administering bar exams is the responsibility of the bar association in the particular state or territory concerned.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Those interested in pursuing a career at the bar must first be admitted as lawyers in the Supreme Court of their home state or territory.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This generally requires the completion of legal studies which can take up to 8 years depending on the mode of study, the particular degree being completed and the law school.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] After completing a law degree, law graduates are then usually required to complete a period of Practical Legal Training (PLT).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] During the PLT period, law graduates are provided with further legal education focusing more on the practical or technical aspects of the law, such as court practice, conveyancing and drafting statements of claim.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Law graduates are also required to complete a minimum number of days under the supervision of a more senior lawyer.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] After the successful completion of practical legal training, law graduates must then apply to be admitted to the Supreme Court in their state or territory.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This ceremony is usually held with the chief justice of the state or territory presiding.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] It is a formal ceremony which also includes taking an oath (or making an affirmation) to uphold the laws of the jurisdiction and results in the person's name being recorded on the Roll of Practitioners in that jurisdiction.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Once admitted, those wishing to practise as barristers must contact the relevant bar association to register and sit the bar exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The frequency and availability of these exams depends on the relevant bar association.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Generally, the bar exams focus on three main areas of practice which are relevant to barristers; namely evidence, procedure and ethics.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The exams are usually administered during the course of a day and comprise a variety of question types, usually answers are given in essay form.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Candidates are informed of their results within a few months and pass rates are very competitive.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Passing the bar exam in and of itself does not automatically allow one to practise as a barrister, in many jurisdictions (such as New South Wales) further requirements apply.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In New South Wales, successful bar exam candidates are required to complete the NSW Bar Association Bar Practice Course (BPC), which despite its name, is a mandatory course required to be taken after passing the bar exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The BPC consists of lectures, assignments and a significant amount of further reading about court procedure and case law.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] At the conclusion of the BPC, candidates are then required to appear in a mock trial, often before real judicial officers, and argue their respective case.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Once satisfied that the candidate has completed these requirements, the NSW Bar Association then provides each candidate with their practising certificate.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Newly called barristers are referred to as readers for a period of usually one year and are required to have at least one tutor who is barrister with at least seven years of call but is not Senior Counsel.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The initial practising certificate often contains restrictions on what type of work readers are permitted to do.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This may include restrictions such as appearing in court alone, undertaking direct access briefs or any other restriction which the bar association deems appropriate.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] After the 12-month period and upon completion of further requirements such as civil and criminal reading to the bar associations satisfaction, readers are then provided with an unrestricted practising certificate and are no longer readers but barristers.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The Order of Attorneys of Brazil (Ordem dos Advogados do Brasil), the Brazilian bar association, administers a bar examination nationwide two to three times a year (usually in January, March and September).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The Bar examination can be taken on the graduation year.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Success in the examination allows one to practice in any court or jurisdiction of the country.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In Canada, admission to the bar is a matter of provincial or territorial jurisdiction.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] All provinces, except for Québec, follow a common law tradition.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Lawyers in every common law province are qualified as both barristers and solicitors, and must pass a Barristers' Examination and Solicitors' Examination administered by the Law Society that governs the legal profession in their respective province or territory.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The common law provinces all require prospective lawyers to complete a term of articles (usually 10 months) after graduation from law school during which they work under the supervision of a qualified lawyer.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The bar exams may be taken after graduation from law school, but before the commencement of articling, or may be taken during or after articling is completed.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Once the barristers' and solicitors' exams have been passed and the term of articles is successfully completed, students may then be called to the bar and admitted to the legal profession as lawyers (barristers and solicitors).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Chinese students seeking to become lawyers are required to pass the National Unified Legal Professional Qualification Examination, administered by the Ministry of Justice.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This exam was created and first administered in 2018 with an annual pass rate of 10% to 15%.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] It is an updated version of the previous Chinese bar exam, administered from 2002-2017.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] These courses are the vocational part of the training required under the rules of the Bar Standards Board and the Solicitors Regulation Authority and are either undertaken on a full-time basis for one year or on a part-time basis over two years.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] After successfully completing these courses, which generally include various examinations and practical ability tests, graduates must secure either a training contract (for those who have completed the LPC) or a pupillage (for those who have completed the BPTC).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] These are akin to articling positions in other jurisdictions and are the final practical stage before being granted full admission to practice.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The general timescale therefore to become fully qualified after entering Law School can range between 6–7 years (assuming no repeats are required).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] However, some controversy remains about the lack of training contracts and pupillages available to graduates even after having completed the LPC/BPTC.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] These courses can vary in cost anywhere from £9,000 to £17,000 and are generally undertaken by students on a private basis making them incur additional costs.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The final debt in student fees alone after having completed the academic and vocational training can range between £20,000-£25,000.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This is set to increase to £40,000-£50,000 for students entering law school.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The *Solicitor Qualifying Examination* (also known as the SQE exam or "super exam") is the common or single route to qualify as a solicitor in England and Wales.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Replacing the Qualified Lawyers Transfer Scheme in September 2021, this is the only English and Welsh bar examination for solicitors.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In France, Law graduates must obtain a vocational degree called *certificat d'aptitude à la profession d'avocat* (or CAPA in everyday speech) in order to practice independently.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The most common way to achieve the CAPA is by training in an *école d'avocats* (Lawyer's School).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This training includes academical and vocational courses and mandatory internships in law firms.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Entrance to Lawyer's School is obtained by competitive examination.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To become a lawyer in Germany, one has to study law at university for five years.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The First Examination is recognised as equivalent to an integrated Master's degree.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] However, it only provides a limited qualification and does not itself permit access to regulated careers in the legal field without further training.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] At the end of this training, candidates must take and pass the Second State Examination in Law (Zweites Staatsexamen).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Successful candidates of the Second Examination are called fully qualified lawyer (Volljurist).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] They may join the bar as an attorney, to become judges and to become state attorneys (public prosecutors).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] There are some other legal or legal-adjacent careers which require additional or different training (namely public notaries and patent lawyers).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To become a lawyer in Ghana, one has to study law at any university that offers the Bachelor of Laws degree.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] After completing the four year law degree, graduates can apply to be enrolled at the Ghana School of Law.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Following two years of professional training, successful students can take their bar examination.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Upon passing the bar examination, an induction and calling to the bar ceremony is held for all graduating students.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In Hungary, the Bar Examination is called "*Jogi Szakvizsga*", can be translated as "Legal Profession Examination".
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To sit for an exam, the candidate needs at least 3 years of daily 8 hours work experience after having a law university degree (masters level).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Constitutional Law, Administrative Law, Labor Law, Social Security Law and Law of the European Union.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The examination conducted is by Bar Council of India.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The candidate will be given certificate of practice and will be eligible to practice in any court in India.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The exam is conducted in 53 cities of India in national and regional languages.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] For eligibility, members should hold a law degree from a recognised institute of law approved by the Bar Council of India, registered with their respective State Bar Councils.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The law profession in the Republic of Ireland is divided into barristers and solicitors.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] King’s Inns run a series of fourteen exams over ten weeks, from March to June each year.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] For those enrolled as students in its one year Barrister-at-Law degree, the course covers skills such as intensive advocacy (including contested advocacy and witness handling), consultation, drafting of legal documents, legal research, opinion writing, practice and procedure.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] For those who fail to meet the requisite 50% pass mark, repeats are held in the following August and September.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Once the candidate has passed, they are required to complete 1 year of unpaid pupillage (also known as “devilling”) with an experienced barrister in order to become a practising barrister.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The candidate may then register with the Bar of Ireland in order to become a member of the Law Library.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] For **solicitors**, there are 8 entrance exams known as the Final Examination - First Part (FE-1) and are conducted by the Law Society of Ireland twice a year.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The FE-1 consists of constitutional law, law of torts, criminal law, contract law, property law, EU law, company law and equity & trusts.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Once a candidate has passed the FE-1, they must secure a training contract and pass the Professional Practice Course (PPC).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Candidates are also required to complete four advanced electives during the course of their traineeship.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The pass rate for these exams is 50% with repeats being held in Autumn.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Once a candidate has passed the FE-1, the PPC and the requisite 2 years of their traineeship, the candidate may then apply to be admitted to the Roll of Solicitors and will be issued a practising certificate, as required by the Law Society of Ireland.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The candidate must pass a battery of examinations for admittance.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The final examinations consist of a written examination followed by an oral examination in front of three judges.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The Bar Exam in Iran is administered by two different and completely separate bodies.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] One is the Bar Association of Iran, known as the Central Bar Association in Tehran, covering every province's certifications.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This body regulates allthe auspices of the country's syndicate of the bars of the country.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The other body is administered by the Judicial System of Iran subject to article 187 of the country's economic, social and cultural development plan.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To receive the license to practice as a "First Degree Attorney" in Iran, an applicant should complete a bachelor of law program.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The official career path starts after passing the Bar Exam and receiving the title of "Trainee at Law".
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The exam is highly competitive and only a certain number of top applicants are admitted annually.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] There have been concerns about the impartiality of the Center of Attorneys in Iran when granting certifications.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Lawyers can only specialize in one area, and requirements typically include a minimum of three years' experience working and other accomplishments like a PhD, publications, teaching experience, or judicial experience.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] After admission to the bar, an 18-month apprenticeship begins which is highly regulated under the auspices of Bar Syndicate Rules and supervision of an assigned First Degree Attorney.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Trainees or apprentices must attend designated courts for designated weeks to hear cases and write case summaries.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] A logbook signed by the judge on the bench has to certify their weekly attendance.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] By the end of the eighteenth month, they are eligible to apply to take the Final Bar Exam by submitting their case summaries, the logbook and a research work pre-approved by the Bar.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] It is noteworthy, however, that during these 18 months, Trainees are eligible to have a limited practice of law under the supervision of their supervising Attorney.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This practice does not include Supreme Court eligible cases and certain criminal and civil cases.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Candidates will be tested on Civil law, Civil Procedure, Criminal law, Criminal Procedure, Commercial Law, Notary (including rules pertaining Official Documents, Land & Real Estate registrations and regulations etc.).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Each exam takes two days, a day on oral examination in front of a judge or an attorney, and a day of essay examination, in which they will be tested on hypothetical cases submitted to them.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Successful applicants will be honoured with the title of "First Degree Attorney", after they take the oath and can practice in all courts of the country including the Supreme Court.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Those who fail must redo the program in full or in part before re-taking the Final Bar Exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In Italy, the Bar Examination is called "*abilitazione all'esercizio della professione forense*".
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To sit for an exam, the candidate needs a 5-year university degree in jurisprudence and 18 months of legal apprenticeship at a law firm with at least 20 court hearings per semester.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The State Bar Exam is composed of two parts: a written exam and an oral exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The written exam is composed of three written tests over three seven-hour days.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The candidate writes two legal briefs, respectively on contracts and torts (and more generally about civil law), and criminal law, and a third court brief on civil, crime, or administrative law.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The candidates who pass the written tests (the pass rates vary from 30% to 50% according to jurisdiction) can sit at an oral exam before a panel of judges, lawyers, and law professors, who interview for about an hour the candidates on six areas of law.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Italian lawyers may represent their clients on any Italian criminal, civil, or administrative court, except the Supreme Court of Cassation for which an additional exam after several years of law practice is required.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The bar exams in Japan yield the fewest successful candidates worldwide.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The old format of the examinations, last held in 2010 saw only 6% passing the exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] With the new format of examinations—even after extensive reforms and a new mandatory duration of graduate school education for a period of two years—the pass rate is only 22%.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Since 2014, candidates are allowed to take the examinations within five years before their right to take the exam is revoked and they either have to return to law school, take the preparatory exam or give up totally.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] It is administered solely by the Ministry of Justice.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Malaysian students are required to pass the Certificate in Legal Practice (CLP), a 9-month post-graduate course and subsequent examination required to become a qualified lawyer.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] A Bachelor of Legal Studies (Hons) from Universiti Teknologi MARA, is also needed to become a qualified lawyer in Malaysia.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The Philippine Bar Examination is a national test administered once every year on the four Sundays of September (September before 2011 and November until 2022).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] It covers eight areas of law: political law, labor law and social legislation, criminal law, civil law, commercial law, taxation law, remedial law, and legal ethics and practical exercises.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] There are selected testing sites around the country’s law schools.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The top achievers by percentage are released every year in the list of top ten to twenty bar passers.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In Poland, the bar examination is taken after graduating from a law faculty at a university.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] It allows a person to undertake practice, the duration of which varies depending on the specialization.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] After the practical period applicants must pass the exam held by the Professional Chambers with assistance from some members of the Ministry of Justice.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The Singapore Bar Examination (Part B) is administered once every year, usually over the course of four days.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The exam is generally held on the last week of November, and is administered by the Singapore Institute of Legal Education (SILE).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] From 2023 the exam will become more stringent and training will be lengthened.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In Singapore, the legal profession is a fused profession, granting the professional qualification of an 'Advocate and Solicitor' to any successful candidate of the Bar Examinations and its practical requirements.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To qualify as a candidate for the Bar Examinations, an aspiring candidate must first be a graduate from a law school or university that is on the approved list of schools mandated by the Ministry of Law.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The candidate must have also attained a Second Class Lower or equivalent classification in their law degrees to qualify for the bar exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The three universities based in Singapore offering a Bachelor of Laws degree are, National University of Singapore, Singapore Management University, and Singapore University of Social Sciences.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] There are presently twenty-seven (27) foreign universities offering an approved Bachelor of Laws degree on the list, hailing from four countries, United Kingdom, Australia, New Zealand, and the United States of America.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Completed a six-month training contract known as the Practice Training Contract with a local law firm, or practice.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Subject to an order from Court, legal trainees who have completed at least three months of their Practice Training Contract, as well as sat for and passed the Singapore Bar Examinations (Part B), are able to seek partial admission to the bar.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] By applying to the Court to be part-called, candidates are granted the right to appear before the Court in specific circumstances.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] All foreign university graduates are also required to complete an additional six-month training known as the Relevant Legal Training, to prove practical competence with a local law firm, or practice.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Both the Relevant Legal Training, and the Singapore Bar Examinations (Part A) must be completed by a candidate before said candidate is allowed to commence either their Practice Training Contract, or sit for the Singapore Bar Examinations (Part B).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] SILE publishes a Commendation List at the end of February of each year to recognise the top performing candidates with two or more subject distinctions in the annual Singapore Bar Examinations (Part B).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The Commendation List is also published annually in the March issue of Singapore Law Gazette.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Some notable alumni of the Commendation List include Goh Yihan.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Lawyers in South Africa are separated as in several other Commonwealth countries, but there is a different naming convention.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Attorneys face clients while advocates face the courts.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Attorneys may appear in some lower courts.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To be admitted as an attorney, one serves "articles" as a candidate attorney with a practising attorney for two years, and then writes a "board exam" set by the relevant provincial Law Society Archived 2016-01-05 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The length of articles may be reduced by attending a practical legal training course or performing community service.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Attorneys may additionally qualify as Notaries and Conveyancers, via the Conveyancing and Notarial Practice Examinations; those with technical or scientific training may further qualify as patent attorneys.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The requirements to enter private practice as an advocate (Junior Counsel) are also twofold: one needs to become a member of a Bar Association by undergoing a period of training (pupilage) for one year with a practicing advocate and one also needs to sit an admission examination.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] On the recommendation of the Bar Councils, an advocate "of proven experience and skill" (at least ten years experience), may be appointed by the President of South Africa as a Senior Counsel (SC; also referred to as a "silk").
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The law regulating admission to practise law ("The Qualifications of Legal Practitioners Amendment Act of 1997") is being revised.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Due to the colonial-era influence, South Korea's bar exam system closely follows that of Japan's.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The new law school system that began in 2009 allows only the graduates of a law school to apply for the bar exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In Spain the examination to be admitted into the legal practice is the All Spain Bar Examination (after which the lawyer's license is obtained).
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The examination is called and conducted by the Ministry of Justice and is the same for all Spain, regardless of which bar association you later join.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] It is called annually (once a year) and takes place at the same time throughout all Spain.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In Thailand, the bar examination is separate from the lawyer licence.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To practice law as a lawyer—i.e. to speak in the court—one must pass a lawyer licence examination and does not need to be called to the bar.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] People take the bar examination to become qualified to take a judge or public prosecutor examination.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] To be called to the bar, one must pass the written exams consisting of four parts as follows.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Criminal law, employment law, constitution law, administrative law, and tax law.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Civil procedure law, bankruptcy and business reorganization law, and the system of the court of justice.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Criminal procedure law, human rights, and law on the evidence.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The parts 1-2 are usually taken in October and the rest are usually taken in March.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] One does not need to pass all four parts in one year.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] After passing all the written exams, there is an oral exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Around 10,000 bar students sit the exam each year.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In 2013, 1,231 students were called to the bar, 111 of whom did it in only one year.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Quite confusingly with international norms, students called to the bar are referred to as *netibandit* (เนติบัณฑิต), which means Barrister-at-Law in English.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The Thai legal profession, however, is a fused one and those with lawyer licenses are able to practice both as barristers and solicitors in the British/Commonwealth sense.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Many students called to the bar choose to become judges or public prosecutors instead of lawyers.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] As the Thai bar examination (administered and awarded by the Thai Bar Association) is separate from the lawyers licensing scheme (administered and awarded by the Lawyers Council of Thailand), this means that judges and public prosecutors belong to a separate licensing organization from lawyers.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] This is unlike in the US where judges and prosecutors most often come from the ranks of senior lawyers and belong to the same bar.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In the United States, bar examinations are administered by agencies of individual states and territories.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In almost all U.S. states and territories, the bar examination is one of several requirements for admission to the bar.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] In most jurisdictions, the examination is two days long and consists of multiple-choice questions, essay questions, and "performance tests" that model certain kinds of legal writing.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The National Conference of Bar Examiners (NCBE) creates several component examinations that are used in varying combinations by all but two jurisdictions, sometimes in combination with locally drafted examination components.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] The main exceptions are Louisiana and Puerto Rico, which follow civil law systems unlike other parts of the United States.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Generally, earning a degree from a law school (or, more rarely, apprenticeship in a law office) is a prerequisite for taking the bar exam.
[src:advokat/bar-examination] Most law school graduates engage in a regimen of study (called "bar review") between graduating from law school and sitting for the bar.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degrees are now, or were once, awarded in the Nordic countries, the Soviet Union, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Scandinavia and the Nordic countries, a candidate degree is a higher professional-level degree which corresponds to five to seven years of studies.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In the Soviet states, a candidate degree was a research degree roughly equivalent to a Doctor of Philosophy degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In the Netherlands and Belgium, it was an undergraduate first-cycle degree roughly comparable with the bachelor's degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The term is derived from the Latin *candida*, meaning white.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Ancient Rome, men running for political office would typically wear togas chalked and bleached to be bright white at speeches, debates, conventions, and other public functions.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The term *candidate* thus came to mean someone who seeks an office of some sort.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Today, the degrees continue to be referred to by their Latin title (c*andidatus* for men, *candidata* for women), with both male and female degree recipients being called *candidates* in English.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Scandinavia, the term was introduced in the early 18th century and initially referred to the higher degrees in theology, law, and medicine.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A candidate's degree in the relevant field (e.g., Candidate of Law) was a requirement for appointment to higher offices in the state administration (*embedded*), including as priests, judges, other state officials, and physicians.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, Norway, and Sweden, the term "candidate" was eventually used for higher professional academic degrees, usually awarded after around five to seven years of studies.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway, only a few Candidate's degrees (such as Candidate of Theology, Candidate of Medicine, and Candidate of Psychology) are still awarded, while in Denmark and Sweden, all Candidate's degrees are retained.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, educational reforms began in 1993 to make bachelor's and master's degrees commonly available as a two-step alternative to the Candidate's degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Despite these reforms, the candidate degree was regarded as the standard academic qualification well into the 21st century.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In 2010, the majority of students completing the required amount of studies necessary for a bachelor's degree continued with their studies to be awarded a candidate's degree, or equivalent, instead.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Because most students continue to achieve this level of study, the labor market in Denmark does not respect bachelor's degrees as a first-cycle degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Many institutions in Denmark which no longer offer the candidate degree as a result of the Bologna Process continue to offer joint bachelor-masters programs which last five years, just as the candidate degree had.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway, the Quality Reform of 2003 enacted the nation's compliance with the Bologna process, and most candidates' degrees are no longer awarded for academic qualifications.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A select number of professional programs, however, have been given an exception from the Bologna process, allowing candidates' degrees to continue to be awarded for specific six-year professional programs.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] As of 2023, the University of Oslo, for example, awards such professional degrees in medicine (*cand.med.*), psychology (*cand.psychol.*), and theology (*cand.theol.*).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In the Netherlands and Belgium, the "Candidate's diploma" was an undergraduate first-cycle diploma that the university issued to students who passed their Candidate's examination.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] After obtaining the certificate, one was entitled to use the academic title *Candidatus* (prenominal abbreviation *Cand.*).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] This was the lowest academic degree that could be achieved in these countries, and is roughly comparable with the bachelor's degree (BA or BSc).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The candidate exam took place after the student completes a substantial and pre-determined part of their university education, in the case of a five-year or more prolonged course, typically after completion of the third year.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Students in a four-year class received the degree at the end of their second or during their third year, depending on the criteria set by the institution.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Candidate's degrees were phased out in the Netherlands in 1982 and have been largely replaced by the bachelor's degree with the introduction of the Bologna Process.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In the Soviet Union, candidate degrees were research degrees roughly equivalent to a Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degrees continue to be awarded in modern Russia and some East European countries which were formerly part of the Soviet Union.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of the Arts (Latin: *Candidatus/candidate magisterii*; abbreviated as *cand.mag*) is an academic degree currently awarded in Denmark.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree is officially translated into English as Master of Arts and requires five years of studies.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It is not to be confused with the magister's degree (*magister artium* or *magister Scientiarum*), a degree requiring 7–8 years of studies with a strong emphasis on the scientific thesis, and which is the approximate equivalent of a PhD degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree was initially introduced in Denmark in 1883.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] For most of its history, the degree usually required between 4 and 5 years of studies.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In its later years, the formal minimum requirement was 3.5 years for the faculties of mathematics and natural sciences, and 4–4.5 for the faculties of humanities and social sciences.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Today, the degree is awarded only in humanities and requires five years of studies.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree was also awarded in Norway beginning in 1920, based on the Danish degree; since 2003, it is no longer awarded.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Arts and Letters (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata* *philologiae*; abbreviated as *cand. philol.*) is an academic degree in Arts and Letters awarded in Denmark.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It is considered an entry-level scientific degree for careers in academia (qualifying for positions as assistant professor or lecturer), as doctorates traditionally are awarded later in the job to senior academics.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree was once awarded in Norway but had also been phased out by 2007.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] At the time, it typically required six years of study at Norwegian universities.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Economics (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata economics*; abbreviated as *cand.oecon.*) is an academic degree in economics currently awarded in Denmark and formerly in Iceland and Norway.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It is roughly equivalent to a Master of Economics.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree was introduced in Norway in 1905 as a supplementary academic degree in economics.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The program usually lasted two years, was conferred by the Faculty of Law, University of Oslo and primarily intended for those already holding a cand.jur. degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The cand.oecon. did not qualify its holder for higher civil servant positions.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In 1934, it became an independent 5-year program in economics.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree was replaced in Norway by the Bachelor/Master's degree system in 2003.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree was first made available at the University of Iceland in 1964 as a 4-year program in Business Administration at the Faculty of Economics and Business Administration.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It was replaced in 1996 by the current bachelor's and master's of science programs.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Information Technology (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata informationis technologiæ*; abbreviated as *cand. it.*) is a graduate degree awarded in Denmark equivalent to a Master of Science in Information Technology.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, the title can be obtained at the IT University of Copenhagen and through It-vest (a collaboration between several Danish universities).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Law (Latin: *candidates/candidate juris*; abbreviated as *cand.jur.*) is both a graduate law degree awarded to law students in the Nordic region as well as an "academic status" designation for advanced Law School students in German-speaking countries.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The Candidate of Law degree was once awarded in Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The application process to study for the degree was highly competitive throughout the Nordic region, as the qualifying exam to practice law could only be taken at a university, where the government officially granted the diploma privilege.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] All Nordic countries—except Denmark—have changed their law degrees from the Candidate to a master's due to the Bologna Process.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Finland, the *Oikeustieteen kandidaatti* (abbreviated OTK; Swedish: *Juris kandidatexamen*, Jur. kand.) was replaced by *Oikeustieteen maisteri* (abbreviated OTM; Swedish: *Juris magister*, JM), which is obtained after five years of law studies (180 + 120 ECTS).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Those previously granted a candidate of law diploma could continue using their previous title in Finland.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Iceland, the *Embættispróf í lögfræði* (*cand. jur.)* degree has been replaced by the *ML í lögfræði* (*mag. jur.)* title.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway, the cand.jur. was formally replaced in 2003 by the *Master i Rettsvitenskap* master's degree, which is obtained after five years of law studies equivalent to 300 ECTS.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The last *cand. jur.* degrees were awarded in Norway in the spring of 2007.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Sweden, the *Jurist kandidatexamen* (*jur. kand.*) degree was replaced by *Juristexamen* in 2010, which is completed after four-and-a-half years of studying at the average pace (270 ECTS).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Previously graduated *jur. kand.* diploma holders were eligible to continue using their title before and after the Bologna process; the academic degree is split into two different diplomas.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Previously, the lower degree was *Varanotaari*, abbreviated VN (Swedish: *Vicenotarie*), and current lower degree *Oikeusnotaari*, shortened ON (Swedish: *Rättsnotarie*, RN) is awarded after completing three years of study (180 ECTS).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Before the Soviet occupation, a post-graduate law degree was awarded as a cand.jur. in Estonia.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] President Konstantin Päts, for example, held a cand. jur. degree from the University of Tartu.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The use of the candidate system in Estonia is tied to the colonial influence of the nordic counties, especially Denmark..
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Estonia, the current post-graduate law degree is *Õigusteaduse magister*.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, the *Juridisk kandidateksamen (cand. jur.)* is obtained after five years of law studies (180 + 120 ECTS).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Undergraduate degree is *Bachelor i jura* (*bac. jur.*) which usually take three years to complete (180 ECTS).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Germany, Austria, and Switzerland, the term "cand. iur." is a designation used in the academic environment by advanced law students.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Instead, the designation is used in an internal university context or the context of publications, for example, contributions to journals or anthologies.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The designation is usually obtained after successful completion of the intermediate examination (after 4 to 6 semesters) and roughly corresponds to the qualification level of a Bachelor of Laws.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Before passing the intermediate examination, law students shall use the designation "stud. iur." (*studiosus iuris*).
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Germany, law school is completed with the passing of the First Law Examination after 4–6 years of study.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Austria, the degree program ends with a diploma examination, and the academic degree "Mag. iur." is awarded.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The academic degree "lic. iur." was abolished during the Bologna reform.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Mathematics and the Natural Sciences (Latin: *Candidatus/candidate realism*; abbreviated as *cand. real.*) is a former academic degree used in Norway and conferred in mathematics and natural sciences.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] There was originally no set duration for the completion of this degree, although 7–8 years was normal, and including a dissertation which usually took between 2 and 4 years to complete.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] As of 1985, the formal requirement amounted to 6 years of studies and dissertation work, although there was a strong tradition for extensive dissertations, leading many students to take longer.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree is sometimes translated as PhD.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Medicine (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata medicinae*; abbreviated as *cand. med.*) is an academic degree awarded in Denmark, Iceland, and Norway following a six-year medical school education.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Medical students in Germany, Austria, and Switzerland carry this title during their medical studies before being awarded the degree of Dr. med.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] (Austria) after defending a doctoral or diploma thesis before a jury.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Along with candidate degrees in veterinary medicine, psychology, and theology, it is one of the few Latin degree titles still awarded in Norway.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Political Science (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata scientiarum politicarum*; abbreviated as *cand.scient.pol.*) is an academic degree in political science, awarded by several Danish universities.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree historically required six years of study, but currently requires five.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The current five-year degree is equivalent to, and is translated into English as, a Master of Science in political science.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Until 2008, the equivalent degree was awarded in Norway as a *cand.polit.* degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Economics (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata politices*; abbreviated as *cand.polit*.) is an academic degree in economics, currently only awarded in Denmark.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, cand.polit. refers exclusively to the Candidate's economics degree awarded by the University of Copenhagen.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Economics degrees from other Danish universities are known as *cand. oecon* and *cand. merc*.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway, the cand.polit. was formerly awarded an academic degree in all social sciences, including economics, psychology, sociology, and political science.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It normally requires at least six years of study, although many students extend this period.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] At the time of its abolition, the cand.polit. degree was in practice a two-year or a two-and-a-half-year extension to the four-year cand.mag. degree or equivalent qualifications.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Following the Quality Reform of 2003, it has been replaced by a Master of Philosophy degree, shortening the nominal study time from six to five years.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Psychology (Latin: *candidatus/candidata psychologiae*; abbreviated as *cand. psych* or *cand.psychol*) is an academic degree in Psychology currently awarded in Denmark and Norway.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, the degree is awarded by the University of Copenhagen, Aarhus University, University of Southern Denmark, and Aalborg University.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway the degree is awarded by the University of Oslo, the Norwegian University of Science and Technology, the University of Bergen, and the University of Tromsø.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In scope and length, it is equivalent to a degree somewhere between a master's and a doctorate in clinical psychology.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It was introduced at the University of Copenhagen in 1944 and at the University of Oslo in 1948 based on the Danish degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, the degree requires five years of studies, while in Norway, it requires five years of academic studies and a one-year internship as part of the studies.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] As part of the Bologna Process, the degree in Denmark consists of a three-year bachelor's degree in psychology followed by a two-year master's degree in clinical psychology that gives the right to use the title *cand.psych*.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Although completion of the degree qualifies the holder to apply for a license as a clinical psychologist, it does not in itself authorize the holder to practice clinical psychology.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway, after the final exam, those with a cand.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] May apply for and will usually be granted the authorization to practice clinical psychology.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, two years of supervised practice is required before full approval.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Science (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata Scientiarum*; abbreviated as *cand.scient.*) is an academic degree currently awarded in Denmark and formerly awarded in Norway.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It is roughly equivalent to a Master of Science degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, cand.scient. is a higher-level degree awarded by Danish universities to graduate students in the mathematics and natural sciences.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The study requires 120 ECTS, which normally requires two years of study and a completed bachelor's degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway, cand.scient. was a higher-level degree awarded in mathematics and natural sciences.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It was introduced in 1985, replacing the more rigorous cand. real. degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Completion required 1.5–2 years of study and a completed cand. mag.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In 2003, the cand.scient. degree was replaced in Norway by the *Master of Science* degree as part of the adoption of the Bologna Process.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Theology (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata theologiæ*; abbreviated as *cand. theol.*) is an academic degree awarded after completion of a six-year higher education program in theology in Iceland, Denmark, and Norway.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The title is protected by law in Denmark and Norway.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Denmark, the title is described as equivalent to Master of Theology, while in Norway, it ranks higher.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway, it is one of the few candidate degree titles to have remained after the Quality Reform of 2003.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] It can only be issued by four institutions: NLA University College, the University of Oslo, the MF Norwegian School of Theology, and VID Specialized University.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] A Candidate of Veterinary Medicine (Latin: *Candidatus/candidata* *medicinae veterinariae*; abbreviated as *cand.med.vet*) is an academic degree awarded in Scandinavian countries following a 5.5 to 6-year veterinary medical school education.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] Equivalent degrees in other countries qualify a student to practice as a veterinarian, such as a Master of Veterinary Science.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] The degree is awarded by the Norwegian University of Life Sciences in Norway, the University of Copenhagen in Denmark, and the Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences in Sweden—the only educational institutions in the Scandinavian countries to offer the veterinary degree.
[src:advokat/candidate-of-law] In Norway, the title is one of the few candidate degrees that has continued to be awarded after the Quality Reform 2003.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland was first settled around 9000 BC after the last Ice Age.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] During the Stone Age, various cultures emerged, distinguished by different styles of ceramics.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Bronze Age and Iron Ages were marked by contacts with other cultures in Fennoscandia and the Baltic region.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] From the late 13th century, Finland became part of Sweden following the Northern Crusades.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In 1809, as a result of the Finnish War, Finland was captured from Sweden and became an autonomous grand duchy within the Russian Empire.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] During this period, Finnish art flourished and an independence movement gradually developed.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Following the Russian Revolution of 1917, Finland declared its independence.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] A civil war ensued the following year, with the anticommunist Whites emerging victorious.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland's status as a republic was confirmed in 1919.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] During World War II, Finland fought against the Soviet Union in the Winter War and the Continuation War, and later against Nazi Germany in the Lapland War.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As a result, it lost parts of its territory to the Soviet Union but retained its independence and democracy.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] During the Cold War, Finland embraced an official policy of neutrality.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After the Cold War, Finland became a member of the European Union in 1995 and the Eurozone in 1999.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Following the Russian invasion of Ukraine, Finland joined NATO in 2023.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland became the first country in Europe to grant universal suffrage in 1906, and the first in the world to give all adult citizens the right to run for public office.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland remained a largely rural and agrarian country until the 1950s, when it pursued rapid industrialisation and a Nordic-style welfare state, resulting in an advanced economy and high per capita income.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The country consistently ranks highly in international rankings across various categories, such as education, economic competitiveness, happiness, and prosperity.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finnish foreign policy based on its middle power status emphasizes international cooperation and partnership, which has recently shifted towards closer ties with NATO.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finnish cultural values, including egalitarianism, secularism, human rights and environmentalism, are actively promoted through membership in multiple international forums.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The name *Suomi* (Finnish for 'Finland') has uncertain origins, but a common etymology with *saame* (the Sámi) has been suggested.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the earliest historical sources, from the 12th and 13th centuries, the term *Finland* refers to the coastal region around Turku in the southwest of modern Finland; this region later became known as Finland Proper in distinction from the country name Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the 14th and 15th centuries, the southwest (Eura and Turku), the interior (around Lake Päijänne), and the southeast (reaching Lake Ladoga) regions of modern Finland were incorporated into the Swedish realm.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The entire area was called *Finlandia et partes orientales* or *Österland* ("Eastland") by the Scandinavians.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The term *Österland* was used until the 16th century.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] By the end of the Middle Ages, the term *Finland* was extended to the east as well.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The area that is now Finland was settled in, at the latest, around 8500 BC during the Stone Age towards the end of the last glacial period.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The artefacts the first settlers left behind present characteristics that are shared with those found in Estonia, Russia, and Norway.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The earliest people were hunter-gatherers, using stone tools.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The first pottery appeared in 5200 BC, when the Comb Ceramic culture was introduced.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The area of present-day Finland was in the western limits of the culture, which produced pottery with a distinct comb pattern.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The arrival of the Corded Ware culture in the south of coastal Finland between 3000 and 2500 BC may have coincided with the start of agriculture.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Even with the introduction of agriculture, hunting and fishing continued to be important parts of the subsistence economy.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Based upon linguistic evidence, Finland seems to have been primarily inhabited by speakers of Paleo-European languages prior to the migration of the Finno-Ugric peoples, which influenced the Sámi languages who were the first Finno-Ugric peoples to move towards Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] These languages have been divided into Paleo-Laplandic languages which were spoken around Lapland, and the Lakelandic languages spoken in most of modern-day Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the Bronze Age, permanent all-year-round cultivation and animal husbandry spread, but the cold climate slowed the change.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Seima-Turbino phenomenon brought the first bronze artefacts to the region and possibly also the Finno-Ugric languages.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Commercial contacts that had so far mostly been to Estonia started to extend to Scandinavia.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Domestic manufacture of bronze artefacts started 1300 BC.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland Proper was the most densely populated area.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Commercial contacts in the Baltic Sea region grew and extended during the eighth and ninth centuries.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Main exports from Finland were furs, slaves, castoreum, and falcons to European courts.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Imports included silk and other fabrics, jewelry, Ulfberht swords, and, in lesser extent, glass.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Production of iron started approximately in 500 BC.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] At the end of the ninth century, indigenous artefact culture, especially weapons and women's jewelry, had more common local features than ever before.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] This has been interpreted to be expressing common Finnish identity.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] An early form of Finnic languages spread to the Baltic Sea region approximately 1900 BC.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Common Finnic language was spoken around Gulf of Finland 2000 years ago.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The dialects from which the modern-day Finnish language was developed came into existence during the Iron Age.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Contacts with the ancient Baltic and eastern Germanic peoples greatly influenced the Proto-Finnic language.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Although distantly related, the Sámi people retained the hunter-gatherer lifestyle longer than the Finns.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Sámi cultural identity and the Sámi languages have survived in Lapland, the northernmost province.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The 12th and 13th centuries were a violent time in the northern Baltic Sea.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Livonian Crusade was ongoing and the Finnish tribes such as the Tavastians and Karelians were in frequent conflicts with Novgorod and with each other.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Also, during the 12th and 13th centuries several crusades from the Catholic realms of the Baltic Sea area were made against the Finnish tribes.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Danes waged at least three crusades to Finland, in 1187 or slightly earlier, in 1191 and in 1202, and Swedes, possibly the so-called second Crusade to Finland, in 1249 against Tavastians and the third Crusade to Finland in 1293 against the Karelians.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The so-called first Crusade to Finland, possibly in 1155, most likely never occurred.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As a result of the Crusades, mostly with the Second Swedish Crusade led by Birger Jarl, and the colonization of some Finnish coastal areas with Christian Swedes during the Middle Ages, Finland gradually became part of the kingdom of Sweden and the sphere of influence of the Catholic Church.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Under Sweden, Finland was annexed as part of the cultural order of Western Europe.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Swedes built fortresses in Häme and Turku, while a Swedish royal council was instituted, an administrative structure and fiscal apparatus was created, and law codes were codified during the reigns of Magnus Ladulås (1275–1290) and Magnus Eriksson (1319–1364).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As a result, the Finnish lands were firmly integrated into the Swedish realm.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Swedish was the dominant language of the nobility, administration, and education; Finnish was chiefly a language for the peasantry, clergy, and local courts in predominantly Finnish-speaking areas.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] During the Protestant Reformation, the Finns gradually converted to Lutheranism.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The end of the Kalmar Union ushered in an era of religious, social, and economic changes.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] 1523–1560) made his second son Johan the duke of Finland, while Gustav Adolf (r.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] 1611–1632) created the office of governor-general for Finland as part of his restructuring of the administration of the Swedish realm.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the 16th century, a bishop and Lutheran Reformer Mikael Agricola published the first written works in Finnish; and Finland's current capital city, Helsinki, was founded by King Gustav Vasa in 1555.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The first university in Finland, the Royal Academy of Turku, was established by Queen Christina of Sweden at the proposal of Count Per Brahe in 1640.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finns reaped a reputation in the Thirty Years' War (1618–1648) as a well-trained cavalrymen called "Hakkapeliitta".
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland suffered a severe famine in 1695–1697, during which about one third of the Finnish population died, and a devastating plague occurred a few years later.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the 18th century, wars between Sweden and Russia twice led to the occupation of Finland by Russian forces, times known to the Finns as the Greater Wrath (1714–1721) and the Lesser Wrath (1742–1743).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] It is estimated that almost an entire generation of young men was lost during the Great Wrath, due mainly to the destruction of homes and farms, and the burning of Helsinki.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Swedish era ended with the Finnish War of 1809.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] On 29 March 1809, after being conquered by the armies of Alexander I of Russia, Finland became an autonomous grand duchy within the Russian Empire, as recognised by the Diet of Porvoo.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] This situation continued until the end of 1917.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In 1812, Alexander I incorporated the Russian province of Vyborg into the Grand Duchy of Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In 1854, Finland became involved in Russia's involvement in the Crimean War when the British and French navies bombed the Finnish coast and Åland during the so-called Åland War.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Although Swedish was still widely spoken, the Finnish language began to gain recognition during this period.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] From the 1860s, a strong Finnish nationalist movement, known as the Fennoman movement, grew.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As a leading Fennoman philosopher and statesman, J.V.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Snellman played a decisive role in the 19th-century Finnish national movement by championing the official status of the Finnish language and spearheading the introduction of the Finnish markka in 1865, thereby strengthening the autonomy of the Grand Duchy of Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Milestones included the publication of what would become Finland's national epic, the *Kalevala*, in 1835 and the legal equality of the Finnish language with Swedish in 1892.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the spirit of Adolf Ivar Arwidsson – "we are not Swedes, we do not want to become Russians, so let us be Finns" – a Finnish national identity was established.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Nevertheless, there was no real independence movement in Finland until the early 20th century.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish famine of 1866–1868 occurred after freezing temperatures in early September devastated crops and killed around 15% of the population, making it one of the worst famines in European history.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The famine led the Russian Empire to relax financial regulations, and investment increased in the following decades.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The gross domestic product (GDP) per capita was still half of that of the United States and a third of that of Britain.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] From 1899 to 1917, the Russian Empire pursued a policy of Russification, which was suspended between 1905 and 1908.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In 1906, universal suffrage was introduced in the Grand Duchy of Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] However, relations between the Grand Duchy of Finland and the Russian Empire soured when the Russian government began to take steps to restrict Finland's special status and autonomy.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] For example, universal suffrage was virtually meaningless in practice, as the tsar did not have to approve any of the laws passed by the Finnish parliament.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The desire for independence gained ground, first among radical liberals and socialists, partly driven by a declaration called the*February Manifesto* by the last tsar of the Russian Empire, Nicholas II, on 15 February 1899.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After the February Revolution of 1917, Finland's position as a Grand Duchy under the rule of the Russian Empire was questioned.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish parliament, controlled by the Social Democrats, passed the so-called Power Act to give the parliament supreme authority.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] This was rejected by the Russian Provisional Government, which decided to dissolve the parliament.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] New elections were held in which the right-wing parties won by a small majority.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Some social democrats refused to accept the result, claiming that the dissolution of parliament and the subsequent elections were extra-legal.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The two almost equally powerful political blocs, the right-wing parties and the Social Democratic Party, were deeply divided.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The October Revolution in Russia changed the geopolitical situation once again.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Suddenly the right-wing parties in Finland began to reconsider their decision to block the transfer of supreme executive power from the Russian government to Finland when the Bolsheviks came to power in Russia.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The right-wing government, led by Prime Minister P.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Svinhufvud, presented the Declaration of Independence on 4 December 1917, which was officially approved by the Finnish Parliament on 6 December.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic (RSFSR), led by Vladimir Lenin was the first country to recognise Finland's independence on 4 January 1918.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] On 27 January 1918, the government began to disarm the Russian forces in Ostrobothnia.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The socialists took control of southern Finland and Helsinki, but the white government continued in exile in Vaasa.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] This led to a short but bitter civil war.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Whites, backed by Imperial Germany, prevailed over the Reds and their self-proclaimed Finnish Socialist Workers' Republic.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After the war, tens of thousands of Reds were interned in camps where thousands were executed or died of malnutrition and disease.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] A deep social and political enmity was sown between the Reds and the Whites that would last until the Winter War and beyond.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The civil war and the activist expeditions to Soviet Russia in 1918–1920, known as the "Kinship Wars", strained relations with the East.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After a brief experiment with monarchy, when an attempt to make Prince Frederick Charles of Hesse the king of Finland failed, a republican constitution was adopted and Finland became a presidential republic, with K.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Ståhlberg elected as its first president on 25 July 1919.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] A liberal nationalist with a legal background, Ståhlberg anchored the state in liberal democracy, promoted the rule of law and initiated internal reforms.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland was also one of the first European countries to strongly promote women's equality, with Miina Sillanpää becoming the first female minister in Finnish history in Väinö Tanner's cabinet in 1926–1927.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish-Russian border was established in 1920 by the Treaty of Tartu, which largely followed the historical border but gave Finland Pechenga (Finnish: *Petsamo*) and its Barents Sea port.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finnish democracy survived Soviet coup attempts and the anti-communist Lapua movement.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In 1917 there were three million people in the country.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After the civil war, a credit-based land reform was introduced, increasing the proportion of the population with access to capital.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] About 70% of the workforce was employed in agriculture and 10% in industry.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Soviet Union and Nazi Germany signed the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact on 23 August 1939, which divided Europe into spheres of influence between the two dictatorships.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In accordance with the pact, the Soviet Union launched the Winter War on 30 November 1939 in order to annex Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish Democratic Republic was set up by Joseph Stalin at the beginning of the war to govern Finland after Soviet conquest.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] There was widespread international condemnation of the unprovoked attack and it led to the Soviet Union being expelled from the League of Nations.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Red Army was defeated in numerous battles, most notably the Battle of Suomussalmi.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After two months of negligible progress on the battlefield, as well as heavy losses in men and material, Soviet forces began to advance in February and reached Vyborg (Finnish: *Viipuri*) in March.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Moscow Peace Treaty was signed on 12 March 1940, and the war ended the following day.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland had defended its independence, but ceded 9% of its territory to the Soviet Union.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Between 1939 and 1944, some 400,000 people were evacuated from Karelia.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Hostilities resumed in June 1941 with the Continuation War, when Finland allied itself with Germany following the latter's invasion of the Soviet Union; the main aim was to regain the territory lost to the Soviets barely a year earlier.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finnish troops occupied Eastern Karelia from 1941 to 1944 and assisted the German Army in the Siege of Leningrad.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The massive Soviet Vyborg–Petrozavodsk offensive in the summer of 1944 led to a breakthrough until the Finns finally repulsed it at Tali–Ihantala.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] This partial Soviet success led to a stalemate and later an armistice.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] This was followed by the Lapland War of 1944–1945, when Finland fought retreating German forces in northern Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Armistice and treaty signed with the Soviet Union in 1944 and 1948 included Finnish obligations, restraints, and reparations, as well as further territorial concessions.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As a result of the two wars, Finland lost 12% of its land area, 20% of its industrial capacity, its second largest city, Vyborg (Finnish: *Viipuri*), and the ice-free port of Liinakhamari (Finnish: *Liinahamari*).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finns lost around 97,000 soldiers and were forced to pay war reparations initially set at $300 million in 1938 prices, later adjusted to $226.5 million.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] However, the country avoided occupation by Soviet forces and managed to retain its independence.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Along with Great Britain, Finland emerged from the war as one of the only European countries to have taken part in hostilities that was never occupied and managed to preserve its democracy throughout.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the decades following World War II, the Communists were a strong political party.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Furthermore, the Soviet Union persuaded Finland to refuse Marshall Plan aid.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] However, in the hope of preserving Finland's independence, the United States provided secret development aid and supported the Social Democratic Party.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The development of trade with the Western powers, such as the United Kingdom, and the payment of reparations to the Soviet Union led to Finland's transformation from a primarily agrarian society to an industrialised one.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Valmet, originally a shipyard and then several metal workshops, was established to produce materials for war reparations.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After the reparations were paid, Finland continued to trade with the Soviet Union as part of bilateral trade.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In 1950, 46% of Finnish workers were employed in agriculture and a third lived in urban areas, but new jobs in manufacturing, services and trade quickly attracted people to the cities.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The average number of births per woman fell from a baby boom peak of 3.5 in 1947 to 1.5 in 1973.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As the baby boomers entered the workforce, the economy failed to create jobs fast enough and hundreds of thousands emigrated to more industrialised Sweden, with emigration peaking in 1969 and 1970.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland participated in trade liberalisation in the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund and the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] During the Cold War, Finland officially embraced a policy of neutrality.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The YYA Treaty (Finno-Soviet Pact of Friendship, Cooperation and Mutual Assistance) recognized Finland's desire to remain outside great-power conflicts.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] From 1956 president Urho Kekkonen had a virtual monopoly on relations with the Soviet Union, which was crucial to his continued popularity.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In politics, there was a tendency to avoid any policy or statement that could be interpreted as anti-Soviet.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] This phenomenon was dubbed "Finlandisation" by the West German press.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] A market economy was maintained in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Various industries benefited from trade privileges with the Soviets.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Economic growth was rapid in the post-war period, and by 1975 Finland's GDP per capita was the 15th highest in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] During the 1970s and 1980s, Finland built one of the most extensive welfare states in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In 1973, Finland negotiated a treaty with the European Economic Community (EEC) that reduced tariffs, enhancing trade relations.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Miscalculated macroeconomic decisions, a banking crisis, the collapse of its largest trading partner, the Soviet Union, and a global economic downturn caused a deep recession in Finland in the early 1990s.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The recession bottomed out in 1993 and Finland enjoyed more than a decade of steady economic growth.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After the collapse of the Soviet Union, Finland began to integrate more closely with the West.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland joined the European Union in 1995 and the euro zone in 1999.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Much of the economic growth of the late 1990s was fuelled by the success of mobile phone manufacturer Nokia.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish people elected Tarja Halonen in the 2000 Presidential election, making her the first female President of Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Her predecessor, President Martti Ahtisaari, later won the Nobel Peace Prize in 2008.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The 2008 financial crisis paralysed Finland's exports in 2008, leading to weaker economic growth throughout the decade.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Sauli Niinistö was elected President of Finland from 2012 until 2024, when Alexander Stubb took over.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finnish support for NATO rose sharply after the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Before February 2022, opinion polls showed a narrow but decisive majority against NATO membership; by April, a supermajority was in favour of membership.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] On 11 May 2022, Finland signed a mutual security pact with the United Kingdom.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] On 12 May, Finland's president and Prime Minister called for NATO membership "without delay".
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Subsequently, on 17 May, the Finnish Parliament voted 188–8 in favour of Finland's accession to NATO.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland became a member of NATO on 4 April 2023.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland is often referred as "the land of a thousand lakes".
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Lying approximately between latitudes 60° and 70° N, and longitudes 20° and 32° E, Finland is one of the world's northernmost countries.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Of world capitals, only Reykjavík lies more to the north than Helsinki.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The country is geographically stretched strongly in a north–south direction: the distance from the southernmost point – Hanko in Uusimaa – to the northernmost – Nuorgam in Lapland – is 1,160 kilometres (720 mi).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland has about 168,000 lakes (of area larger than 500 m2 or 0.12 acres) and 179,000 islands.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Its largest lake, Saimaa, is the fourth largest in Europe.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish Lakeland is the area with the most lakes in the country; many of the major cities in the area, most notably Tampere, Jyväskylä and Kuopio, are located near the large lakes.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Lying off the coast of Finland is the world's largest archipelago, a formation consisting of more than 50,000 islands.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The greatest concentration of these islands is found in the southwest in a part of the Baltic Sea called the Archipelago Sea, between continental Finland and the island of Åland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Much of the geography of Finland is a result of the Ice Age.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The glaciers were thicker and lasted longer in Fennoscandia compared with the rest of Europe.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The eroding effects have contributed to a mostly flat landscape in Finland, characterized by hills.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] However, in the northern regions, including areas bordering the Scandinavian Mountains, the terrain features mountainous elevations.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] At 1,324 metres (4,344 ft), Halti is the highest point in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] It is found in the north of Lapland at the border between Finland and Norway.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The highest mountain whose peak is entirely in Finland is Ridnitšohkka at 1,316 m (4,318 ft), directly adjacent to Halti.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The retreating glaciers have left the land with terminal moraine deposits.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] These are ridges of stratified gravel and sand, running northwest to southeast, where the ancient edge of the glacier once lay.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Among the biggest of these are the three Salpausselkä ridges that run across southern Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Having been compressed under the enormous weight of the glaciers, terrain in Finland is rising due to the post-glacial rebound.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The effect is strongest around the Gulf of Bothnia, where land steadily rises about 1 cm (0.4 in) a year.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As a result, the old sea bottom turns little by little into dry land: the surface area of the country is expanding by about 7 square kilometres (2.7 sq mi) annually.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Relatively speaking, Finland is rising from the sea.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The landscape is covered mostly by coniferous taiga forests and fens, with little cultivated land.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Of the total area, 10% is lakes, rivers, and ponds, and 78% is forest.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The forest consists of pine, spruce, birch, and other species.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland is the largest producer of wood in Europe and among the largest in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The most common type of rock is granite.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] It is a ubiquitous part of the scenery, visible wherever there is no soil cover.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Moraine or till is the most common type of soil, covered by a thin layer of humus of biological origin.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Podzol profile development is seen in most forest soils except where drainage is poor.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Gleysols and peat bogs occupy poorly drained areas.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Phytogeographically, Finland is shared between the Arctic, central European, and northern European provinces of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] According to the WWF, the territory of Finland can be subdivided into three ecoregions: the Scandinavian and Russian taiga, Sarmatic mixed forests, and Scandinavian Montane Birch forest and grasslands.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Taiga covers most of Finland from northern regions of southern provinces to the north of Lapland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] On the southwestern coast, south of the Helsinki-Rauma line, forests are characterized by mixed forests, that are more typical in the Baltic region.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the extreme north of Finland, near the tree line and Arctic Ocean, Montane Birch forests are common.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 5.08/10, ranking it 109th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Similarly, Finland has a diverse and extensive range of fauna.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] There are at least sixty native mammalian species, 248 breeding bird species, over 70 fish species, and 11 reptile and frog species present today, many migrating from neighbouring countries thousands of years ago.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Large and widely recognized wildlife mammals found in Finland are the brown bear, grey wolf, wolverine, and elk.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Three of the more striking birds are the whooper swan, a large European swan and the national bird of Finland; the Western capercaillie, a large, black-plumaged member of the grouse family; and the Eurasian eagle-owl.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The latter is considered an indicator of old-growth forest connectivity, and has been declining because of landscape fragmentation.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Around 24,000 species of insects are prevalent in Finland some of the most common being hornets with tribes of beetles such as the Onciderini also being common.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The most common breeding birds are the willow warbler, common chaffinch, and redwing.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Of some seventy species of freshwater fish, the northern pike, perch, and others are plentiful.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Atlantic salmon remains the favourite of fly rod enthusiasts.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The endangered Saimaa ringed seal, one of only three lake seal species in the world, exists only in the Saimaa lake system of southeastern Finland, down to only 390 seals today.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The species has become the emblem of the Finnish Association for Nature Conservation.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] A third of Finland's land area originally consisted of moorland, about half of this area has been drained for cultivation over the past centuries.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The main factor influencing Finland's climate is the country's geographical position between the 60th and 70th northern parallels in the Eurasian continent's coastal zone.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the Köppen climate classification, the largest part of Finland lies in the boreal zone, characterized by warm summers and freezing winters.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Within the country, the temperateness varies considerably between the southern coastal regions and the extreme north, showing characteristics of both a maritime and a continental climate.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland is near enough to the Atlantic Ocean to be continuously warmed by the Gulf Stream.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Gulf Stream combines with the moderating effects of the Baltic Sea and numerous inland lakes to explain the unusually warm climate compared with other regions that share the same latitude, such as Alaska, Siberia, and southern Greenland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Even in the south, the harshest winter nights can see the temperatures fall to −30 °C (−22 °F), although on coastal areas like Helsinki, temperatures below −30 °C (−22 °F) are rare.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Climatic summers (when mean daily temperature remains above 10 °C or 50 °F) in southern Finland last from about late May to mid-September, and in the inland, the warmest days of July can reach over 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Although most of Finland lies on the taiga belt, the southernmost coastal regions are sometimes classified as hemiboreal.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In northern Finland, particularly in Lapland, the winters are long and cold, while the summers are relatively warm but short.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] On the most severe winter days in Lapland can see the temperature fall to −45 °C (−49 °F).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The winter of the north lasts for about 200 days with permanent snow cover from about mid-October to early May.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Summers in the north are quite short, only two to three months, but can still see maximum daily temperatures above 25 °C (77 °F) during heat waves.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] No part of Finland has Arctic tundra, but Alpine tundra can be found at the fells Lapland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish climate is suitable for cereal farming only in the southernmost regions, while the northern regions are suitable for animal husbandry.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] A quarter of Finland's territory lies within the Arctic Circle and the midnight sun can be experienced for more days the farther north one travels.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] At Finland's northernmost point, the sun does not set for 73 consecutive days during summer and does not rise at all for 51 days during winter.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland is ranked 4th in Environmental Performance Index for year 2024.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] This Index combines various indicators around known issues around the world and measures how good they fit in among each countries on a scale.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland scores good in parameters like Climate Change Mitigation, Waste Management, Air pollution, Air quality etc.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Modern Finnish values are rooted in egalitarian ideals.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The country maintains a Nordic welfare model with significant state intervention in critical economic sectors.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Robust LGBT rights, strong efforts to eliminate poverty, broad protections for women's rights, secularism, and environmentalism are indicators of its political and cultural values.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Constitution of Finland defines the political system; Finland is a parliamentary republic within the framework of a representative democracy.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Prime Minister is the country's most powerful person.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Citizens can run and vote in parliamentary, municipal, presidential, and European Union elections.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland's head of state is the President of the Republic.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland had, for most of its independence a semi-presidential system of government, but in the last few decades the powers of the president have become more circumscribed, and consequently the country is now considered a parliamentary republic.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] A new constitution, enacted in 2000, made the presidency primarily a ceremonial office.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The president appoints the prime minister as elected by Parliament, appoints and dismisses the other ministers of the Finnish Government on the recommendation of the prime minister, opens parliamentary sessions, and confers state honors.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Nevertheless, the president remains responsible for Finland's foreign relations, including the making of war and peace, but excluding matters related to the European Union.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Moreover, the president exercises supreme command over the Finnish Defence Forces as commander-in-chief.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the exercise of his or her foreign and defense powers, the president is required to consult the Finnish government, but the government's advice is not binding.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In addition, the president has several domestic reserve powers, including the authority to veto legislation, to grant pardons, and to appoint several public officials.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The president is also required by the Constitution to dismiss individual ministers or the entire government upon a parliamentary vote of no confidence.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The president is directly elected via runoff voting and may serve for a maximum of two consecutive 6-year terms.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The current president is Alexander Stubb, who took office on 1 March 2024.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The 200-member unicameral Parliament of Finland (Finnish: *Eduskunta*) exercises supreme legislative authority in the country.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] It may alter the constitution and ordinary laws, dismiss the cabinet, and override presidential vetoes.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Its acts are not subject to judicial review; the constitutionality of new laws is assessed by the parliament's constitutional law committee.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The parliament is elected for a term of four years using the proportional D'Hondt method within several multi-seat constituencies through the most open list multi-member districts.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Various parliament committees listen to experts and prepare legislation.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Significant parliamentary parties are Centre Party, Christian Democrats, Finns Party, Green League, Left Alliance, National Coalition Party, Social Democrats and Swedish People's Party.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After parliamentary elections, the parties negotiate among themselves on forming a new cabinet (the Finnish Government), which then has to be approved by a simple majority vote in the parliament.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The cabinet can be dismissed by a parliamentary vote of no confidence, although this rarely happens, as the parties represented in the cabinet usually make up a majority in the parliament.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The cabinet exercises most executive powers and originates most of the bills that the parliament then debates and votes on.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] It is headed by the Prime Minister of Finland, and consists of him or her, other ministers, and the Chancellor of Justice.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Each minister heads his or her ministry, or, in some cases, has responsibility for a subset of a ministry's policy.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] After the prime minister, the most powerful minister is often the minister of finance.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As no one party ever dominates the parliament, Finnish cabinets are multi-party coalitions.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As a rule, the post of prime minister goes to the leader of the biggest party and that of the minister of finance to the leader of the second biggest.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Orpo Cabinet is the incumbent 77th government of Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The cabinet is headed by Petteri Orpo and is a coalition between the National Coalition Party, Finns Party, the Swedish People's Party, and the Christian Democrats.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The local administrative divisions of the country are the municipalities (*kunta*, *kommun*), which may also call themselves cities (*kaupunki*, *stad*).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] As of 2021, there are 309 municipalities.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Most are small with median number of 6,000 residents.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The highest decision-making authority is the municipal council, whose members are elected for a four-year term.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The municipal elections, which are based on a partisan list, provide a democratic counterbalance for the political composition of the parliament.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The municipalities account for half of the public spending, financed by municipal income tax, state subsidies, and other revenue.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The main duties of the municipalities include education and child care services; cultural, youth, library and sports services; urban planning and land use; water and waste management and environmental services.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The 2023 reform transformed the administrative system from a two-tier structure (central government and municipal level) into a three-tier system.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The 21 wellbeing services counties occupy the middle level as regional democratic self-governing entities.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] They are responsible for organising health, social welfare and emergency services.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Wellbeing services counties do not have the right to levy taxes and their funding is based on central government funding.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The City of Helsinki and the region of Åland remain outside the wellbeing services county structure.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The municipalities in mainland Finland are grouped into 18 regions (*maakunta*, *landskap*).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The regions are governed by regional councils, which serve as forums of cooperation for the municipalities.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Regional council members are selected from among the members of the municipal councils.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The statutory functions of the regions are regional development and regional land-use planning.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] They also responsible for the coordination of EU structural funds.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The autonomous province of Åland forms its own region, with a democratically elected regional parliament (*lagting*).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The state administration also has a regional presence through which ministries and central agencies operate at a regional level.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] These agencies are distinct from the self-governing regional level.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The two main state regional authorities are the Regional State Administrative Agencies (*Aluehallintovirasto* or *AVI*) and the Centres for Economic Development, Transport and the Environment (*Elinkeino-, liikenne- ja ympäristökeskus* or *ELY-keskus*).
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The 6 Regional State Administrative Agencies in mainland Finland carry out regional implementation, steering, and enforcement of relevant legislation, including supervision, permit and subsidy processes, and coordinating contingency planning. Åland is designated a seventh county.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The 15 Centres for Economic Development, Transport and the Environment in mainland Finland are primarily development-oriented organizations that also have implementation dimensions.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Their work is divided into three areas: business and industry, transport and infrastructure, and environment and natural resources.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Sámi people have a semi-autonomous Sámi native region in Lapland for issues on language and culture.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The judicial system of Finland is a civil law system divided between courts with regular civil and criminal jurisdiction and administrative courts with jurisdiction over litigation between individuals and the public administration.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finnish law is codified and based on Swedish law and in a wider sense, civil law or Roman law.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The court system for civil and criminal jurisdiction consists of local courts, regional appellate courts, and the Supreme Court.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The administrative branch of justice consists of administrative courts and the Supreme Administrative Court.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In addition to the regular courts, there are a few special courts in certain branches of administration.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] There is also a High Court of Impeachment for criminal charges against certain high-ranking officeholders.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Around 92% of residents have confidence in Finland's security institutions.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The overall crime rate of Finland is not high in the EU context.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Some crime types are above average, notably the high homicide rate for Western Europe.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] A day fine system is in effect and also applied to offenses such as speeding.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland has a very low number of corruption charges; Transparency International ranks Finland as one of the least corrupt countries in Europe.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland's middle power status includes a strong economy, international cooperation, and commitment to human rights.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] According to the 2012 constitution, the president leads foreign policy in cooperation with the government, except that the president has no role in EU affairs.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In 2008, president Martti Ahtisaari was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, Finland is the 13th most peaceful country in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish Defence Forces consists of an army, navy, and air force.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The border guard, while under the Ministry of the Interior, can be incorporated into the Defence Forces during wartime.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland maintains universal male conscription, under which all male Finnish nationals above 18 years of age serve for 6 to 12 months of armed service or 12 months of civilian (non-armed) service.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The Finnish military comprises a cadre of professional soldiers (mainly officers and technical personnel), conscripts, and a large number of reservists.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The standard readiness strength is 34,700 people in uniform, of which 25% are professional soldiers; the entire reserve comprises approximately 900,000 people.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Voluntary post-conscription overseas peacekeeping service is popular, and troops serve around the world in UN, NATO, and EU missions.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Women are allowed to serve in all combat arms; in 2022, 1,211 women entered voluntary military service.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finnish defence expenditure per capita is one of the highest in the European Union.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] With a high capability of military personnel, arsenal and homeland defence willingness, Finland is one of Europe's militarily strongest countries.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The NATO organization will site a command unit at Riihimäki in 2027.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland became a member of NATO on 4 April 2023, though it had previously participated in the NATO Response Force.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland is actively involved in multilateral military operations, including the Joint Expeditionary Force (JEF), the EU Battlegroup, and the Kosovo Force; it also contributed to the International Security Assistance Force in Afghanistan.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] On 18 December 2023, Finland signed the Defense Cooperation Agreement (DCA) with the United States, which regulates the presence of the U.S. armed forces and their dependents on Finnish territory and the presence and activities of U.S. defence suppliers.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland has one of the world's most extensive welfare systems, one that guarantees decent living conditions for all residents.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] The welfare system was created almost entirely during the first three decades after World War II.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Section 6 of the Finnish Constitution states: "No one shall be placed in a different position on situation of sex, age, origin, language, religion, belief, opinion, state of health, disability or any other personal reason without an acceptable reason".
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Finland has been ranked above average among the world's countries in democracy, press freedom, and human development.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] Amnesty International has expressed concern regarding some issues in Finland, such as the imprisonment of conscientious objectors, and societal discrimination against Romani people and members of other ethnic and linguistic minorities.
[src:advokat/finland-p01] In the report of the European umbrella organization ILGA-Europe published in May 2023, Finland ranked sixth in a European comparison of LGBTQ+ rights.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2022, Finland ranked 16th globally in nominal GDP per capita according to the IMF.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Additionally, Finland boasts a well-developed welfare system that encompasses free education and universal healthcare, contributing to its reputation as a wealthy nation.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2018, the service sector constituted the largest segment of the economy, amounting to 66% of the GDP, while manufacturing and refining made up 31%.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Primary production accounted for 2.9% of the economy.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Manufacturing is the primary economic sector concerning foreign trade.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The predominant industrial sectors in 2007 were electronics (22%), machinery, vehicles, and other engineered metal products (21.1%), forest industry (13%), and chemicals (11%).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The gross domestic product reached its peak in 2021.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland has been ranked seventh in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland has considerable timber, mineral (including iron, chromium, copper, nickel and gold) and freshwater resources.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's gold production in 2015 was 9 metric tons.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] For the rural population, forestry, paper mills and agriculture are important.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Helsinki metropolitan area accounts for roughly one-third of Finland's GDP.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Private services represent the largest employer in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's soil and climate pose particular challenges for crop production, with harsh winters and relatively short growing seasons, often interrupted by frost.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] However, the prevalence of the Gulf Stream and the North Atlantic Drift Current in Finland's temperate climate allows for half of the world's arable land north of the 60° north latitude.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Although annual precipitation is generally adequate, it mostly transpires during winter, which poses a continuous risk of summer droughts.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Farmers have adapted to the climate by relying on quick-ripening and frost-resistant crop varieties.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] They cultivate south-facing slopes and rich bottomlands to ensure year-round production, even during summer frosts.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Drainage systems are often utilized to remove excess water.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's agricultural sector has demonstrated remarkable efficiency and productivity, particularly in comparison to its European counterparts.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Forests are crucial to the nation's economy, making it one of the world's foremost wood producers and offering raw materials at competitive prices to the wood processing industries.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The government has played an important role in forestry for a considerable period similar to that in agriculture.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] It has regulated tree cutting, sponsored technical improvements, and established long-term plans to guarantee the sustainability of the country's forests in supplying the wood-processing industries.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2008, the average level of income, adjusted for purchasing power, was comparable to that of Italy, Sweden, Germany and France.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2006, 62% of the labour force was employed by firms with fewer than 250 workers, which generated 49% of total business revenue.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Gender segregation between male-dominated professions and female-dominated professions is higher than in the US.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The proportion of part-time workers was one of the lowest in OECD in 1999.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2013, the 10 largest private sector employers in Finland were Itella, Nokia, OP-Pohjola, ISS, VR, Kesko, UPM-Kymmene, YIT, Metso, and Nordea.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2022, the unemployment rate was 6.8%.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2024, 47% of households consisted of a single person, 32% two persons and 21% three or more persons.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The average residential space was 40 square metres (430 sq ft) per person.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2023, Finland's GDP reached €273 billion.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2022, altogether 74 per cent of employed persons worked in services and administration, 21 per cent in industry and construction, and four per cent in agriculture and forestry.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2018, Finland had the highest concentration of cooperatives relative to its population.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The largest retailer, which is also the largest private employer, S-Group, and the largest bank, OP Financial Group, in Finland are both cooperatives.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The free and largely privately owned financial and physical Nordic energy markets traded in NASDAQ OMX Commodities Europe and Nord Pool Spot exchanges, have provided competitive prices compared with other EU countries.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2022, Finland has the lowest non-household electricity prices in the EU.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2021, the energy market was around 87 terawatt hours and the peak demand around 14 gigawatts in winter.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Industry and construction consumed 43.5% of total consumption, a relatively high figure reflecting Finland's industries.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's hydrocarbon resources are limited to peat and wood.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] About 18% of the electricity is produced by hydropower In 2021, renewable energy (mainly hydropower and various forms of wood energy) was high at 43% compared with the EU average of 22% in final energy consumption.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] About 20% of electricity is imported, especially from Sweden due to its lower cost there.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of February 2022, Finland's strategic petroleum reserves held 200 days worth of net oil imports in the case of emergencies.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland has five privately owned nuclear reactors producing 40% of the country's energy.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] There are three reactors at the Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant and two old Soviet-designed VVER-440 at the Loviisa Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Onkalo spent nuclear fuel repository is under construction at the Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant in the municipality of Eurajoki, on the west coast of Finland, by the company Posiva.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] operates a railway network serving all major cities in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's road system is utilized by most internal cargo and passenger traffic.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The annual state operated road network expenditure of around €1 billion is paid for with vehicle and fuel taxes which amount to around €1.5 billion and €1 billion, respectively.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Among the Finnish highways, the most significant and busiest main roads include the Turku Highway (E18), the Tampere Highway (E12), the Lahti Highway (E75), and the ring roads (Ring I and Ring III) of the Helsinki metropolitan area and the Tampere Ring Road of the Tampere urban area.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The main international passenger gateway is Helsinki Airport, which handled about 15.3 million passengers in 2023.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Another 26 airports have scheduled passenger services.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Helsinki Airport-based Finnair, Blue1, and Nordic Regional Airlines, Norwegian Air Shuttle sell air services both domestically and internationally.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Government annually spends around €350 million to maintain the 5,865-kilometre-long (3,644 mi) network of railway tracks.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Rail transport is handled by the state-owned VR Group.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's first railway was opened in 1862, and today it forms part of the Finnish Main Line, which is more than 800 kilometers long.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Helsinki opened the world's northernmost metro system in 1982.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The majority of international cargo shipments are handled at ports.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Vuosaari Harbour in Helsinki is the largest container port in Finland; others include Kotka, Hamina, Hanko, Pori, Rauma, and Oulu.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] There is passenger traffic from Helsinki and Turku, which have ferry connections to Tallinn, Mariehamn, Stockholm and Travemünde.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Helsinki-Tallinn route is one of the busiest passenger sea routes in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland rapidly industrialized after World War II, achieving GDP per capita levels comparable to that of Japan or the UK at the beginning of the 1970s.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Initially, most of the economic development was based on two broad groups of export-led industries, the "metal industry" (*metalliteollisuus*) and "forest industry" (*metsäteollisuus*).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The "metal industry" includes shipbuilding, metalworking, the automotive industry, engineered products such as motors and electronics, and production of metals and alloys including steel, copper and chromium.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Many of the world's biggest cruise ships, including MS Freedom of the Seas and the Oasis of the Seas have been built in Finnish shipyards.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The "forest industry" includes forestry, timber, pulp and paper, and is often considered a logical development based on Finland's extensive forest resources, as 73% of the area is covered by forest.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the pulp and paper industry, many major companies are based in Finland; Ahlstrom-Munksjö, Metsä Board, and UPM are all Finnish forest-based companies with revenues exceeding €1 billion.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] However, in recent decades, the Finnish economy has diversified, with companies expanding into fields such as electronics (Nokia), metrology (Vaisala), petroleum (Neste), and video games (Rovio Entertainment), and is no longer dominated by the two sectors of metal and forest industry.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Likewise, the structure has changed, with the service sector growing.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Despite this, production for export is still more prominent than in Western Europe, thus making Finland possibly more vulnerable to global economic trends.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2023, the Finnish economy was estimated to consist of approximately 2.3% agriculture, 23.9% manufacturing, and 61.4% services.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2019, the per-capita income of Finland was estimated to be $48,869.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2020, Finland was ranked 20th on the ease of doing business index, among 190 jurisdictions.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish politicians have often emulated the Nordic model.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Nordics have been free-trading for over a century.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The level of protection in commodity trade has been low, except for agricultural products.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland is ranked 13th in the 2025 global Index of Economic Freedom and ninth in Europe.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] According to the OECD, only four EU-15 countries have less regulated product markets and only one has less regulated financial markets.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The 2024 IMD World Competitiveness Yearbook ranked Finland 15th most competitive.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The World Economic Forum 2019 index ranked Finland the eleventh most competitive.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The legal system is clear and business bureaucracy less than most countries.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Property rights are well protected and contractual agreements are strictly honoured.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland is rated the least corrupt country in the world in the Corruption Perceptions Index and 20th in the Ease of doing business index.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In Finland, collective labour agreements are universally valid.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] These are drafted every few years for each profession and seniority level, with only a few jobs outside the system.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The agreement becomes universally enforceable provided that more than 50% of the employees support it, in practice by being a member of a relevant trade union.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The unionization rate is high (70%), especially in the middle class (AKAVA, mostly for university-educated professionals: 80%).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2017, tourism in Finland grossed approximately €15.0 billion.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Of this, €4.6 billion (30%) came from foreign tourism.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2017, there were 15.2 million overnight stays of domestic tourists and 6.7 million overnight stays of foreign tourists.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Tourism contributes roughly 2.7% to Finland's GDP.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Lapland has the highest tourism consumption of any Finnish region.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Above the Arctic Circle, in midwinter, there is a polar night, a period when the sun does not rise for days or weeks, or even months, and correspondingly, midnight sun in the summer, with no sunset even at midnight (for up to 73 consecutive days, at the northernmost point).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Lapland is so far north that the aurora borealis, fluorescence in the high atmosphere due to solar wind, is seen regularly in the fall, winter, and spring.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish Lapland is also locally regarded as the home of Santa Claus, with several theme parks, such as Santa Claus Village and Santa Park in Rovaniemi.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Other significant tourist destinations in Lapland also include ski resorts (such as Levi, Ruka and Ylläs) and sleigh rides led by either reindeer or huskies.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Tourist attractions in Finland include the natural landscape found throughout the country as well as urban attractions.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland contains 40 national parks (such as Koli National Park in North Karelia), from the Southern shores of the Gulf of Finland to the high fells of Lapland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Outdoor activities range from Nordic skiing, golf, fishing, yachting, lake cruises, hiking, and kayaking, among many others.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Bird-watching is popular for those fond of avifauna, however, hunting is also popular.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The most famous tourist attractions in Helsinki include the Helsinki Cathedral and the Suomenlinna sea fortress.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The most well-known Finnish amusement parks include Linnanmäki in Helsinki and Särkänniemi in Tampere.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Olaf's Castle (*Olavinlinna*) in Savonlinna hosts the annual Savonlinna Opera Festival, and the medieval milieus of the cities of Turku, Rauma and Porvoo also attract spectators.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Commercial cruises between major coastal and port cities in the Baltic region play a significant role in the local tourism industry.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The population of Finland is approximately 5.7 million.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The birth rate is 7.8 per 1,000 inhabitants, giving a fertility rate of 1.26 children born per woman, one of the lowest in the world and well below the replacement rate of 2.1.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 1887, Finland recorded its highest rate, with 5.17 children born per woman.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The child mortality rate is 2.1 deaths per every 1,000 births, one of the lowest in the world; this is attributed to a strong medical system and robust maternal care initiatives, including the maternity package programme.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland has one of the oldest populations in the world, with a median age of 44.1 years and 23.8% of the population aged 65 and over.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland has an average population density of 19 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] This is the third lowest population density in Europe, after Norway and Iceland, and the lowest in the European Union.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's population has always been concentrated in the southern parts of the country, a phenomenon that became more pronounced during the urbanisation of the 20th century.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Three of Finland's four largest cities are located in the Helsinki Metropolitan Area: Helsinki, Espoo and Vantaa.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The city of Tampere is third after Helsinki and Espoo, and Vantaa is fourth.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Other cities with more than 100,000 inhabitants are Turku, Oulu, Jyväskylä, Kuopio and Lahti.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's immigrant population is growing.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2025, there were 660,800 people with a foreign background living in Finland (11.7% of the population), most of them from the former Soviet Union, Estonia, Ukraine, Iraq, Somalia, China and India.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The children of foreigners are not automatically granted Finnish citizenship, as Finnish citizenship law maintains a policy of *jus sanguinis*, whereby only children born to at least one Finnish parent are granted citizenship.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] If they are born in Finland and cannot obtain citizenship of another country, they become Finnish citizens.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In addition, certain people of Finnish descent living in countries that were once part of the Soviet Union retain the right of return, i.e. the right to establish permanent residence in the country, which would eventually entitle them to citizenship.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2025, 10.9% of the Finnish population were foreign born.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As a result of recent immigration, the country has significant populations of ethnic Estonians, Russians, Ukrainians, Iraqis, Chinese, Somalis, Filipinos, Indians and Iranians.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's national minorities include the Sámi, Roma, Jews and Tatars.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Roma of the Finnish Kale group settled in the country at the end of the 16th century.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish and Swedish are the official languages of Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish predominates nationwide while Swedish is spoken in some coastal areas in the west and south (with towns such as Ekenäs, Pargas, Närpes, Kristinestad, Jakobstad and Nykarleby.) and in the autonomous region of Åland, which is the only monolingual Swedish-speaking region in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As of 2025, the native language of 83.5% of the population was Finnish, which is part of the Finnic subgroup of the Uralic language.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The language is one of only four official EU languages not of Indo-European origin, and has no relation through descent to the other national languages of the Nordics.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Conversely, Finnish is closely related to Estonian and Karelian, and more distantly to Hungarian and the Sámi languages.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Swedish is the native language of 5.0% of the population (Swedish-speaking Finns).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Swedish is a compulsory school subject and general knowledge of the language is good among many non-native speakers.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Likewise, a majority of Swedish-speaking non-Ålanders can speak Finnish.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Finnish side of the land border with Sweden is unilingually Finnish-speaking.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Swedish across the border is distinct from the Swedish spoken in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] There is a sizeable pronunciation difference between the varieties of Swedish spoken in the two countries, although their mutual intelligibility is nearly universal.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish Romani is spoken by some 5,000–6,000 people; there are 13,000-14,000 Romani people in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Romani and Finnish Sign Language are also recognized in the constitution.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] There are two sign languages: Finnish Sign Language, spoken natively by 4,000–5,000 people, and Finland-Swedish Sign Language, spoken natively by about 150 people.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Tatar is spoken by a Finnish Tatar minority of about 800 people whose ancestors moved to Finland mainly between the 1870s and 1920s.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Sámi languages have an official status in parts of Lapland, where the Sámi, numbering over 10,000 are recognized as an indigenous people.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] About a quarter of them speak a Sámi language as their mother tongue.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Sámi languages that are spoken in Finland are Northern Sami, Inari Sami, and Skolt Sami.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The rights of minority groups (in particular Sami, Swedish speakers, and Romani people) are protected by the constitution.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Nordic languages and Karelian are also specially recognized in parts of Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] English is studied by most pupils as a compulsory subject from the first grade (at seven years of age), formerly from the third or fifth grade, in the comprehensive school (in some schools other languages can be chosen instead).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] German, French, Spanish and Russian can be studied as second foreign languages from the fourth grade (at 10 years of age; some schools may offer other options).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] With 3.5 million members, the Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland is Finland's largest religious body; As of 2025, 61.2% of Finns were members of the church.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland has seen its share of the country's population declining by roughly one percent annually in recent years.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The decline has been due to both church membership resignations and falling baptism rates.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The second largest group, accounting for 35.9% of the population, has no religious affiliation.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] A small minority belongs to the Finnish Orthodox Church (1.0%).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Other Protestant denominations and the Roman Catholic Church are significantly smaller, as are the Jewish and other non-Christian communities (totalling 1.6%).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Pew Research Center estimated the Muslim population at 2.7% in 2016.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's state church was the Church of Sweden until 1809.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] As an autonomous Grand Duchy under Russia from 1809 to 1917, Finland retained the Lutheran State Church system, and the Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland was established.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] After Finland had gained independence in 1917, religious freedom was declared in the constitution of 1919, and a separate law on religious freedom in 1922.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Through this arrangement, the Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland gained a constitutional status as a national church alongside the Finnish Orthodox Church, whose position however is not codified in the constitution.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The main Lutheran and Orthodox churches have special roles such as in state ceremonies and schools.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2016, 69.3% of Finnish children were baptized, but by 2019, this figure had declined to around 62% and 82.3% were confirmed in 2012 at the age of 15, and over 90% of the funerals are Christian.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] However, the majority of Lutherans attend church only for special occasions like Christmas ceremonies, weddings, and funerals.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Lutheran Church estimates that approximately 1.8% of its members attend church services weekly.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The average number of church visits per year by church members is approximately two.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] According to a 2010 Eurobarometer poll, 33% of Finnish citizens responded that they "believe there is a God"; 42% answered that they "believe there is some sort of spirit or life force"; and 22% that they "do not believe there is any sort of spirit, God, or life force".
[src:advokat/finland-p02] According to ISSP survey data (2008), 8% consider themselves "highly religious", and 31% "moderately religious".
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the same survey, 28% reported themselves as "agnostic" and 29% as "non-religious".
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Life expectancy was 79 years for men and 84.2 years for women in 2023.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The under-five mortality rate was 2.3 per 1,000 live births in 2022, ranking Finland's rate among the lowest in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The fertility rate in 2023 stood at 1.26 children born/per woman and has been below the replacement rate of 2.1 since 1969.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] With a low birth rate women also become mothers at a later age, the mean age at first live birth being 30.3 in 2023.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] A 2011 study published in *The Lancet* medical journal found that Finland had the lowest stillbirth rate out of 193 countries.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] There has been a slight increase or no change in welfare and health inequalities between population groups in the 21st century.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Lifestyle-related diseases are on the rise.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] More than half a million Finns suffer from diabetes, type 1 diabetes being globally the most common in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Many children are diagnosed with type 2 diabetes.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The number of musculoskeletal diseases and cancers are increasing, although the cancer prognosis has improved.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Allergies and dementia are also growing health problems in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] One of the most common reasons for work disability are due to mental disorders, in particular depression.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Without age standardization, the suicide rates were 13 per 100 000 in 2015, close to the North European average.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Age-standardized suicide rates are still among the highest among developed countries in the OECD.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] There are 307 residents for each doctor.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] About 19% of health care is funded directly by households and 77% by taxation.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In April 2012, Finland was ranked second in Gross National Happiness in a report published by The Earth Institute.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Since 2012, Finland has every time ranked at least in the top 5 of world's happiest countries in the annual World Happiness Report by the United Nations, as well as ranking as the happiest country since 2018.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Most pre-tertiary education is arranged at the municipal level.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Around 3 percent of students are enrolled in private schools (mostly specialist language and international schools).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Formal education is usually started at the age of 7.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Primary school takes normally six years and lower secondary school three years.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The curriculum is set by the Ministry of Education and Culture and the Education Board.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Education is compulsory between the ages of 7 and 18.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] After lower secondary school, graduates may apply to trade schools or gymnasiums (upper secondary schools).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Trade schools offer a vocational education: approximately 40% of an age group choose this path after the lower secondary school.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Academically oriented gymnasiums have higher entrance requirements and specifically prepare for Abitur and tertiary education.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Graduation from either formally qualifies for tertiary education.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In tertiary education, two mostly separate and non-interoperating sectors are found: the profession-oriented polytechnics and the research-oriented universities.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Education is free and living expenses are to a large extent financed by the government through student benefits.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] There are 15 universities and 24 Universities of Applied Sciences (UAS) in the country.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The University of Helsinki is ranked 117th in the Top University Ranking of 2025.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Other reputable universities of Finland include Aalto University in Espoo, both University of Turku and Åbo Akademi University in Turku, University of Jyväskylä, University of Oulu, LUT University in Lappeenranta and Lahti, University of Eastern Finland in Kuopio and Joensuu, and Tampere University.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The World Economic Forum ranks Finland's tertiary education No.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Around 33% of residents have a tertiary degree, similar to Nordics and more than in most other OECD countries except Canada (44%), United States (38%) and Japan (37%).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In addition, 38% of Finland's population has a university or college degree, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Adult education appears in several forms, such as secondary evening schools, civic and workers' institutes, study centres, vocational course centres, and folk high schools.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] More than 30% of tertiary graduates are in science-related fields.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Forest improvement, materials research, environmental sciences, neural networks, low-temperature physics, brain research, biotechnology, genetic technology, and communications showcase fields of study where Finnish researchers have had a significant impact.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland is highly productive in scientific research.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2005, Finland had the fourth most scientific publications per capita of the OECD countries.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 2007, 1,801 patents were filed in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Written Finnish can be said to have existed since Mikael Agricola translated the New Testament into Finnish during the Protestant Reformation in the 16th century.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] However, few notable works of literature were produced until the 19th century, which marked the emergence of a Finnish national Romantic Movement.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] This period prompted Elias Lönnrot to collect Finnish and Karelian folk poetry and to arrange and publish them as the *Kalevala*, the Finnish national epic.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The era saw a rise of poets and novelists writing in Finnish, most notably the national writer Aleksis Kivi (*The Seven Brothers*), as well as Minna Canth, Eino Leino, and Juhani Aho, who was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Literature twelve times.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Alongside Finnish-language literature, many authors of the national awakening wrote in Swedish.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Prominent among them were the national poet Johan Ludvig Runeberg (*The Tales of Ensign Stål*) and Zachris Topelius, whose works occupy a central place in Finland-Swedish literature.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Following Finland's independence, modernist tendencies gained prominence.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] This development was exemplified by the Finland-Swedish poet Edith Södergran, while Finnish-language authors increasingly explored national, historical, and social themes.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] From the 1950s onwards, Finnish poetry embraced modernism, beginning with Paavo Haavikko.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In contemporary Finnish literature, a wide range of genres and styles coexist.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Detective fiction and popular literature have enjoyed particular success.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] At the same time, the Finland-Swedish writer and artist Tove Jansson has become one of Finland's most internationally recognised authors.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Best known as the creator of *The Moomins*, she is among the most translated Finnish writers, and her work has had a lasting impact on Finnish and international popular culture, extending far beyond literature into visual media, museums, and other cultural forms.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The visual arts in Finland started to form their characteristics in the 19th century when Romantic nationalism was rising in autonomous Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The best known Finnish painters, Akseli Gallen-Kallela, started painting in a naturalist style but moved to national romanticism.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Other notable painters of the era include Pekka Halonen, Eero Järnefelt, Helene Schjerfbeck and Hugo Simberg.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the late 20th century, the homoerotic art of Touko Laaksonen, pseudonym Tom of Finland, found a worldwide audience.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's best-known sculptor of the 20th century was Wäinö Aaltonen, remembered for his monumental busts and sculptures.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The works of Eila Hiltunen and Laila Pullinen exemplifies the modernism in sculpture.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finns have made major contributions to handicrafts and industrial design: among the internationally renowned figures are Timo Sarpaneva, Tapio Wirkkala and Ilmari Tapiovaara.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish architecture is famous around the world, and has contributed significantly to several styles internationally, such as Jugendstil (or Art Nouveau), Nordic Classicism and functionalism.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Among the top 20th-century Finnish architects to gain international recognition are Eliel Saarinen and his son Eero Saarinen.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Architect Alvar Aalto is regarded as among the most important 20th-century designers in the world; he helped bring functionalist architecture to Finland, but soon was a pioneer in its development towards an organic style.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Aalto is also famous for his work in furniture, lamps, textiles, and glassware, which were usually incorporated into his buildings.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish folk music can be divided into Nordic dance music and the older tradition of poem singing, poems from which the national epic, the *Kalevala*, was created.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Much of Finland's classical music is influenced by traditional Finnish and Karelian melodies and lyrics, as comprised in the *Kalevala*.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the historical region of Finnish Karelia, as well as other parts of Eastern Finland, the old poem singing traditions were preserved better than in the western parts of the country.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the 19th century Nordic folk dance music largely replaced the kalevaic tradition.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish folk music has undergone a roots revival and has become a part of popular music.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The people of northern Finland, Sweden, and Norway, the Sámi, are known primarily for highly spiritual songs called joik.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The first Finnish opera was written by the German-born composer Fredrik Pacius in 1852.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Pacius also wrote the music to the poem *Maamme/Vårt land* (Our Country), Finland's national anthem.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the 1890s Finnish nationalism based on the *Kalevala* spread, and Jean Sibelius became famous for his vocal symphony *Kullervo*.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In 1899 he composed *Finlandia*, which played an important role in Finland gaining independence.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] He remains one of Finland's most popular national figures.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Alongside Sibelius, the distinct Finnish style of music was created by Oskar Merikanto, Toivo Kuula, Erkki Melartin, Leevi Madetoja and Uuno Klami.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Important modernist composers include Einojuhani Rautavaara, Aulis Sallinen and Magnus Lindberg, among others.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Kaija Saariaho was ranked the world's greatest living composer in a 2019 composers' poll.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Many Finnish musicians have achieved international success.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Among them are the conductor Esa-Pekka Salonen, the opera singer Karita Mattila and the violinist Pekka Kuusisto.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] During the 1970s, progressive rock group Wigwam and rock and roll group Hurriganes gained respect abroad.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Finnish punk scene produced some internationally acknowledged names including Terveet Kädet in the 1980s.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Hanoi Rocks was a pioneering glam rock act.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Many Finnish metal bands have gained international recognition; Finland has been often called the "Promised Land of Heavy Metal" because there are more than 50 metal Bands for every 100,000 inhabitants – more than any other nation in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Modern Finnish popular music includes a number of prominent rock musicians, pop musicians, jazz musicians, hip-hop performers, and dance music acts.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland has won the Eurovision Song Contest once in 2006 when Lordi won the contest with the song ''Hard Rock Hallelujah''.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Finnish pop artist Käärijä also got second place in the contest in 2023 with his worldwide hit song ''Cha Cha Cha''.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the film industry, notable modern directors include brothers Mika and Aki Kaurismäki, Dome Karukoski, Antti Jokinen, Jalmari Helander, and Renny Harlin.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Some Finnish drama series are internationally known, such as *Bordertown*.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] A 2022 action film *Sisu*, directed by Jalmari Helander, has achieved the status of the most successful Finnish film of all time in the United States, measured at the box office, with revenues of over $7 million.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In Finland, the most significant films in Finnish history includes *The Unknown Soldier* (1955) and *Here, Beneath the North Star* (1968), both directed by Edvin Laine.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Today, there are around 200 newspapers, 320 popular magazines, 2,100 professional magazines, and 67 commercial radio stations.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The largest newspaper is *Helsingin Sanomat*, its circulation being 339,437 as of 2019.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Yle, the Finnish Broadcasting Company, operates five television channels and thirteen radio channels.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Each year, around 12,000 book titles are published.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Thanks to its emphasis on transparency and equal rights, Finland's press has been rated the freest in the world.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Worldwide, Finns, along with other Nordic peoples and the Japanese, spend the most time reading newspapers.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In regards to telecommunication infrastructure, Finland is ranked third, below the United States and Singapore in the Portulan Institute's Network Readiness Index (NRI) – an indicator for determining the development level of a country's information and communication technologies.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Finns' love for saunas is generally associated with Finnish cultural tradition.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Sauna is a type of dry steam bath practiced widely in Finland, which is especially evident in the strong tradition around Midsummer and Christmas.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The word sauna is of Proto-Finnish origin (found in Finnic and Sámi languages) dating back 7,000 years.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Steam baths have been part of European tradition elsewhere as well, but the sauna has survived best in Finland, in addition to Sweden, Estonia, Latvia, Russia, Norway, and parts of the United States and Canada.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Moreover, nearly all Finnish houses have either their own sauna or in multi-story apartment houses, a timeshare sauna.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Municipal swimming halls and hotels have often their own saunas.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The Finnish sauna culture is inscribed on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish cuisine generally combines traditional country fare and contemporary style cooking.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Potato, meat and fish play a prominent role in traditional Finnish dishes.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish foods often use wholemeal products (rye, barley, oats) and berries (such as bilberries, lingonberries, cloudberries, and sea buckthorn).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Milk and its derivatives like buttermilk are commonly used as food and drink.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The most popular fish food in Finland is salmon.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland has the world's second highest per capita consumption of coffee.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Milk consumption is also high, at an average of about 112 litres (25 imp gal; 30 US gal), per person, per year.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] There are several holidays in Finland, of which perhaps the most characteristic of Finnish culture include Christmas (*joulu*), Midsummer (*juhannus*), May Day (*vappu*) and Independence Day (*itsenäisyyspäivä*).
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Of these, Christmas and Midsummer are special in Finland because the actual festivities take place on eves, such as Christmas Eve and Midsummer's Eve, while Christmas Day and Midsummer's Day are more consecrated to rest.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Other public holidays in Finland are New Year's Day, Epiphany, Good Friday, Easter Sunday and Easter Monday, Ascension Day, All Saints' Day and Saint Stephen's Day.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] All official holidays in Finland are established by Acts of Parliament.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Various sporting events are popular in Finland.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Pesäpallo, the Finnish equivalent of American baseball, is the national sport of Finland, although the most popular sport in terms of spectators is ice hockey.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Other popular sports include athletics, cross-country skiing, ski jumping, football, volleyball, and basketball.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Association football is the most played team sport in terms of the number of players in the country.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland's national basketball team has received widespread public attention.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In terms of medals and gold medals won per capita, Finland is the best-performing country in Olympic history.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland first participated as a nation in its own right at the Olympic Games in 1908.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] At the 1912 Summer Olympics, three gold medals were won by the original "Flying Finn" Hannes Kolehmainen.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the 1920s and '30s, Finnish long-distance runners dominated the Olympics, with Paavo Nurmi winning a total of nine Olympic gold medals and setting 22 official world records between 1921 and 1931.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Nurmi is often considered the greatest Finnish sportsman and one of the greatest athletes of all time.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The 1952 Summer Olympics were held in Helsinki.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] The javelin throw event has brought Finland nine Olympic gold medals, five world championships, five European championships, and 24 world records.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finland also has a notable history in figure skating.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish skaters have won 8 world championships and 13 junior world cups in synchronized skating.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Finnish competitors have achieved significant success in motorsport.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In the World Rally Championship, Finland has produced eight world champions, more than any other country.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] In Formula One, Finland has won the most world championships per capita, with Keke Rosberg, Mika Häkkinen and Kimi Räikkönen all having won the title.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Some of the most popular recreational sports and activities include Nordic walking, running, cycling and skiing.
[src:advokat/finland-p02] Floorball is the most popular youth and workplace sport.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Finnish is typologically agglutinative and uses almost exclusively suffixal affixation.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Nouns, adjectives, pronouns, numerals and verbs are inflected depending on their role in the sentence.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Sentences are normally formed with subject–verb–object word order, although the extensive use of inflection allows them to be ordered differently.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Word order variations are often reserved for differences in information structure.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Finnish orthography uses a Latin-script alphabet derived from the Swedish alphabet, and is phonemic to a great extent.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Vowel length and consonant length are distinguished, and there are a range of diphthongs, although vowel harmony limits which diphthongs are possible.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Finnish belongs to the Finnic branch of the Uralic language family; as such, it is one of the few European languages that is not Indo-European.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The Finnic branch also includes Estonian and a few minority languages spoken around the Baltic Sea and in Russia's Republic of Karelia.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The closest relative of Finnish is either Ingrian, or depending on the definition, Karelian.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Finnic languages form a dialect continuum, where for instance Finnish and Estonian are not separated by any single isogloss that would separate dialects considered "Finnish" from those considered "Estonian", despite the two standard languages being not mutually intelligible.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Several theories exist as to the geographic origin of the most recent common ancestor of Finnish and the other Uralic languages (Proto-Uralic).
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The most widely held view is that it originated somewhere in the boreal forest belt around the Ural Mountains region and/or the bend of the middle Volga.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The strong case for Proto-Uralic is supported by common vocabulary with regularities in sound correspondences, as well as by the fact that the Uralic languages have many similarities in structure and grammar.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Despite having overlapping geographical distributions, Finnic languages and Sami languages are not closely related, and the hypothesis of a separate taxonomic "Finno-Samic" node is controversial.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The Defense Language Institute in Monterey, California, United States, classifies Finnish as a level III language (of four levels) in terms of learning difficulty for native English speakers.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Finnish is spoken by about five million people, most of whom reside in Finland.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] There are also notable Finnish-speaking minorities in Sweden, Norway, Russia, Estonia, Brazil, Canada, and the United States.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The majority of the population of Finland (90.37% as of 2010) speak Finnish as their first language.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The remainder speak Swedish (5.42%), one of the Sámi languages (for example Northern, Inari, or Skolt), or another language as their first language.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Finnish is spoken as a second language in Estonia by about 167,000 people.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The Finnic varieties found in Norway's Finnmark (namely Kven) and in northern Sweden (namely Meänkieli) have the status of official minority languages, and thus can be considered distinct languages from Finnish.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] However, since these languages are mutually intelligible, one may alternatively view them as dialects of the same language.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] No language census exists for Norway, neither for Kven, standard Finnish, or combined.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] As of 2023, 7,454 first- or second-generation immigrants from Finland were registered as having Norwegian residency, while as of 2021, 235 Finns were registered as foreigners studying at Norwegian higher education.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Great Norwegian Encyclopedia estimates Kven speakers at 2,000-8,000.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Altogether, this results in a total amount of Finnish-speakers roughly between 7,200 and 15,600.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] In the latest census, around 1000 people in Russia claimed to speak Finnish natively; however, a larger amount of 14,000 claimed to be able to speak Finnish in total.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] There are also forms of Finnish spoken by diasporas outside Europe, such as American Finnish, spoken by Finnish Americans, and Siberian Finnish, spoken by Siberian Finns.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Today, Finnish is one of two official languages of Finland (the other being Swedish), and has been an official language of the European Union since 1995.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] However, the Finnish language did not have an official status in the country during the period of Swedish rule, which ended in 1809.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] After the establishment of the Grand Duchy of Finland, and against the backdrop of the Fennoman movement, the language obtained its official status in the Finnish Diet of 1863.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Finnish also enjoys the status of an official minority language in Sweden.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Under the Nordic Language Convention, citizens of the Nordic countries speaking Finnish have the opportunity to use their native language when interacting with official bodies in other Nordic countries without being liable to any interpretation or translation costs.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] However, concerns have been expressed about the future status of Finnish in Sweden, for example, where reports produced for the Swedish government during 2017 show that minority language policies are not being respected, particularly for the 7% of Finns settled in the country.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] The Uralic family of languages, of which Finnish is a member, are hypothesized to derive from a single ancestor language termed Proto-Uralic, spoken sometime between 8,000 and 2,000 BCE (estimates vary) in the vicinity of the Ural Mountains.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Over time, Proto-Uralic split into various daughter languages, which themselves continued to change and diverge, yielding yet more descendants.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] One of these descendants is the reconstructed Proto-Finnic, from which the Finnic languages developed.
[src:advokat/finnish-language-p01] Current models assume that three or more Proto-Finnic dialects evolved during the first millennium BCE.
